eam of the Year (2000s)#FA Premier League 3|2001\u201302 Premier League]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/1930394.stm |title=PFA's Premiership XI |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 April 2002 |accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref> [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#Championship 4|2012\u201313 Championship]]<ref name=BBC290413>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22331030 |title=Gareth Bale wins PFA Player of Year and Young Player awards |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 April 2013 |accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thesaintshub.com/waynebridge.html Wayne Bridge Career Profile]\n* {{FIFA player|186443}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/bsp/hi/football/statistics/players/b/bridge_152983.stm BBC profile]\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{Englandstats|id=1115}}\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303005920/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=7858&cc=5739 |title=ESPN profile |date=3 March 2010}}\n* [https://www.premierleague.com/players/1458/Wayne-Bridge/overview Premier League profile]\n* {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319022435/http://www.whufc.com/articles/wayne-bridge-west-ham_2228487_5975 |title=West Ham United profile |date=19 March 2011}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads\n|bg        = white\n|fg        = #CF081F\n|bordercolor = #0B0B3F\n|list1=\n{{England squad 2002 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{England squad UEFA Euro 2004}}\n{{England squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|title= Awards\n|list1=\n{{2001\u201302 Premier League Team of the Year}}\n{{2012\u201313 Football League Championship PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Southampton F.C. Player of the Season}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridge, Wayne}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Southampton]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Winchester]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fulham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Ham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Reading F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2004 players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English association football player}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Wayne Bridge\n|image               = WayneBridge.jpg\n|image_size          = 200\n| alt                =\n|caption             = Wayne Bridge playing for [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2008\n|fullname            = Wayne Michael Bridge<ref name=\"FIFA 2006 squads\">{{cite web |title=2006 FIFA World Cup Germany List of Players |url=https://www.fifadata.com/document/fwc/2006/PDF/FWC_2006_SquadLists.pdf |website=FIFA.com |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1980|8|5|df=y}}<ref name=\"FIFA 2006 squads\"/>\n|birth_place = [[Southampton]], England\n|height              = {{height|m=1.80}}<ref name=SW/>\n|currentclub         = \n|clubnumber          = \n|position            = [[Left back]]\n|youthyears1         =           |youthclubs1 = Olivers Battery\n|youthyears2         = 1996\u20131998 |youthclubs2 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n|years1              = 1998\u20132003 |clubs1 = [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]                   |caps1 = 151 |goals1 = 2\n|years2              = 2003\u20132009 |clubs2 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]                           |caps2 = 87  |goals2 = 1\n|years3              = 2006      |clubs3 = \u2192 [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] (loan)                    |caps3 = 12  |goals3 = 0\n|years4              = 2009\u20132013 |clubs4 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]           |caps4 = 42  |goals4 = 0\n|years5              = 2011      |clubs5 = \u2192 [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] (loan)  |caps5 = 15  |goals5 = 0\n|years6              = 2012      |clubs6 = \u2192 [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] (loan)          |caps6 = 8   |goals6 = 0\n|years7              = 2012\u20132013 |clubs7 = \u2192 [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] (loan) |caps7 = 37   |goals7 = 3\n|years8              = 2013\u20132014     |clubs8 = [[Reading F.C.|Reading]]                           |caps8 = 12  |goals8 = 0 <!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES & GOALS ONLY -->\n| totalcaps = 364 | totalgoals = 6\n|nationalyears1      = 1998\u20131999 |nationalteam1 = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]<ref>[http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersB/BioBridgeW.html England Players \u2013 Wayne Bridge] England Football Online</ref>\n|nationalcaps1 = 3  |nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2      = 1999\u20132001 |nationalteam2 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n|nationalcaps2 = 8  |nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3      = 2002\u20132009 |nationalteam3 = [[England national football team|England]]\n|nationalcaps3 = 36 |nationalgoals3 = 1\n}}\n\n'''Wayne Michael Bridge''' (born 5 August 1980) is an English retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[left back]].\n\nA graduate of the [[Southampton F.C. Academy|Southampton Academy]] where he made his debut in 1998, Bridge also played for [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]], [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] during his [[Premier League]] career.\n\nBridge made 36 appearances for the [[England national football team|England national team]] between 2002 and 2009, being selected for two [[FIFA World Cup]] squads and [[UEFA Euro 2004]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Southampton===\nBridge was born in [[Southampton]], but moved to [[Olivers Battery]], [[Winchester]], at an early age. He attended Oliver's Battery Primary and [[Kings' School]], Winchester.<ref name=\"ITN\"/> When playing for [[Olivers Battery F.C.|Olivers Battery]] he was spotted by [[Micky Adams]], who recommended him to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]], who signed him as a trainee in July 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Fresh-start-players-says-Adams/article-1060991-detail/article.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120912130546/http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/portvale/Port-Vale-Fresh-start-players-says-Adams/article-1060991-detail/article.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=12 September 2012 |title=Port Vale: Fresh start for players, says Adams|last=Shaw|first=Steve|date=9 June 2009|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=9 June 2009}}</ref> He made his reserve team debut, as a [[Striker (association football)|centre-forward]] against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on 13 August 1997<ref>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=466}}</ref> and turned professional in January 1998.<ref name=\"ITN\"/>\n\nBridge made his first-team debut on 16 August 1998 (the opening day of the [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399 season]]) coming on as a replacement for [[John Beresford (footballer)|John Beresford]], who had badly damaged his knee.<ref>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=256}}</ref> Bridge made his first senior start in the next match on 22 August in a 5\u20130 defeat away to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]. As Southampton struggled to pick up points (with only two points after the first nine games), Bridge played (on the left wing) in most of Saints' league games until early December before losing his place to [[Hassan Kachloul]]. For the remainder of the [[1998\u201399 FA Premier League|1998\u201399 Premier League season]], Bridge was only used occasionally as Saints narrowly avoided relegation. He completed his first season as a first-team player with 15 starts and eight substitute appearances.<ref>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=259}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1999\u20132000 in English football#Premier League|following season]] carried on in a similar vein with Bridge making occasional appearances on the left wing until injuries to [[Francis Benali]] and the poor form of his intended replacement [[Patrick Colleter]] gave Bridge the opportunity to play at left-back, where he soon became a fixture in the Saints starting line-up. In the [[1999\u20132000 FA Premier League|1999\u20132000 season]], he made 15 starts (plus four substitute appearances)<ref>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=264}}</ref> scoring his first senior goal, with a powerful free-kick over the wall, in the final match of the season on 14 May 2000 against [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]], as a result of which Wimbledon were relegated to Division 1 after 14 years in the top flight.<ref>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=263}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301 season]], Bridge was an ever-present at left-back as Saints finished their final season at [[The Dell (Southampton)|The Dell]] in tenth place in the [[FA Premier League 2000\u201301|Premier League table]]. Bridge was rewarded by being voted the Southampton Player of the Year for the 2000\u201301 season.<ref>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=269}}</ref>\n\nBridge was \"fast, determined, skilful and full of youthful promise\" and \"his forward runs became an exciting sight at The Dell and then at St Mary's.\"<ref name=\"ITN\">{{cite book | author=Duncan Holley & Gary Chalk |   title=In That Number \u2013 A post-war chronicle of Southampton FC  | publisher=Hagiology Publishing | year=2003 | isbn=0-9534474-3-X|  page=488}}</ref>  He was an ever-present yet again in the following season as Saints again finished their [[2001\u201302 in English football|first season]] at their new [[St Mary's Stadium|stadium]] comfortably in mid-table.<ref>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=277}}</ref>\n\nBridge's temperament and consistency, together with a high level of fitness, enabled him to continue to play every match until 18 January 2003 when he limped off with an injury in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref name = ITN280/> This brought to an end a run of 113 consecutive appearances, a Premier League record for an outfield player (since surpassed by [[Frank Lampard|Frank Lampard, Jr.]]).<ref>{{cite news|date=26 February 2005 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20050226/ai_n11827963 |title=FOOTBALL: THE STATISTICS \u2013 Lampard's longevity has some way to go |work=The Independent |location=UK |accessdate=7 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208234149/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20050226/ai_n11827963 |archivedate= 8 December 2008 }}</ref> His run started on 4 March 2000, from when Bridge played 10,160 consecutive minutes of Premier League football, not missing any play through injury or suspension.<ref name = ITN280>{{cite book |   title=In That Number  | isbn= |  page=280}}</ref>\n\nBy now, bigger clubs were trailing Bridge, and he was finally tempted away to join [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]7&nbsp;million in the 2003 close season.<ref name=ITN/> His last appearance for the club came in the [[FA Cup Final 2003|2003 FA Cup Final]] defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. During his five years as a Saints first-team player, he made 173 appearances, with two league goals against Wimbledon<ref>{{cite news  |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/748208.stm|title=Dons down as Bradford survive|publisher=BBC Sport   |date=14 May 2000 |accessdate=29 December 2009}}</ref> and [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2272632.stm\n|title=Djorkaeff spares Bolton's blushes|publisher=BBC Sport   |date=28 September 2002 |accessdate=29 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Chelsea===\n\n====2003\u201304 season====\nAfter five years with the Saints, Bridge moved to Chelsea in July 2003 for a fee of \u00a37&nbsp;million plus [[Graeme Le Saux]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://superengland.com/sport/content/view/34/37/ |title=Factfile : Wayne Bridge |publisher=superengland.com |accessdate=6 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629122617/http://superengland.com/sport/content/view/34/37/ |archivedate=29 June 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and was initially a regular starter. His finest moment came in the Champions League quarter-final against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2003\u201304. Bridge scored the winning goal in the 88th minute to send Chelsea into the semi-finals and end an 18-game winless run against Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/3593083.stm |title=Arsenal 1\u20132 Chelsea |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=6 September 2007 | date=6 April 2004}}</ref> The goal was later voted goal of the season. Bridge also scored against [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/3300433.stm\n|title=Chelsea overwhelm Besiktas\n|publisher=BBC Sport\n|date=9 December 2003 |accessdate=8 September 2009}}</ref> and [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3349111.stm\n|title=Chelsea 3\u20130 Portsmouth\n|publisher=BBC Sport\n|date=28 December 2003 |accessdate=8 September 2009}}</ref> in the 2003\u201304 season.\n\n====2004\u201305 season====\nBridge started the [[2004\u201305 Chelsea F.C. season|2004\u201305 season]] playing regularly under new manager [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]], but he picked up a serious ankle injury in an [[FA Cup]] tie against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 20 February 2005.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/feb/21/match.newcastleunited\n|title=Chelsea are caught cold by Kluivert and injuries\n|publisher=BBC Sport\n|date=21 February 2005 |accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref> This ended his season and also meant he missed the following weekend's [[2005 Football League Cup Final|League Cup Final]]. Chelsea went on to win the [[Premier League]] in his absence but Bridge had already made enough appearances (15) to receive a winners' medal.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|15061|2004|name=Wayne Bridge|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2005\u201306 season====\nFor the [[2005\u201306 Chelsea F.C. season|2005\u201306 season]], Chelsea signed Spanish left-back [[Asier del Horno]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/4083412.stm |title=Chelsea complete Del Horno switch |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=6 September 2007 | date=21 June 2005}}</ref> and Bridge faced a challenge to get back into the side when he recovered from the injury that kept him out of the team in the latter stages of the 2004\u201305 campaign. He only made two appearances for Chelsea that season, both in domestic cup games.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|15061|2005|name=Wayne Bridge|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref> These limited first team opportunities saw him join [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on loan on 19 January 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=357161&root=england&cc=5739 |title=England \u2013 Through the closed window |publisher=ESPNsoccernet |accessdate=6 September 2007 }}</ref> He made his debut in a 2\u20131 defeat to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]]. The move seemed to benefit him as he managed to secure his place in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] English squad for the tournament in Germany. Chelsea won the Premier League again, but Bridge was not eligible for a medal this time as he had not made a single league appearance for them all season.\n\n====2006\u201307 season====\nBridge's main competition for the Chelsea left back position then came from fellow England international left back [[Ashley Cole]]. Bridge played the full match in Chelsea's 3\u20130 victory over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on the opening day of the [[2006\u201307 Premier League]] season, providing a telling cross for the third goal, scored by a header from [[Didier Drogba]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4786589.stm |title=Chelsea 3\u20130 Man City |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=6 September 2007 | date=20 August 2006 |first=John |last=Sinnott}}</ref> His strong early season form, however, was not enough to hold down the left-back position, with Mourinho preferring Ashley Cole in most games. Following Cole's injury in the 3\u20130 Premier League win against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] early in 2007, Bridge became Chelsea's natural choice for left-back.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6309645.stm |title=Chelsea 3\u20130 Blackburn |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=6 September 2007 | date=31 January 2007 |first=Mandeep |last=Sanghera}}</ref>\n\nBridge featured in attack for an injury struck Chelsea side against [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in the 2007 semi-final 1st leg League Cup match, scoring one goal in the process.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/6236711.stm |title=Wycombe 1\u20131 Chelsea |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=6 September 2007 | date=10 January 2007 |first=Chris |last=Bevan}}</ref>\n\nBridge finished the 2006\u201307 season with two cup final winner's medals after playing in both the [[2007 League Cup Final|League Cup Final]] against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in a 2\u20131<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/6371613.stm |title=Chelsea 2\u20131 Arsenal |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=18 December 2008 | date=25 February 2007}}</ref> win and in the [[2007 FA Cup Final|FA Cup Final]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/6649815.stm|title=Chelsea 1\u20130 Manchester United |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=18 December 2008 | date=19 May 2007 |first=Andrew |last=McKenzie}}</ref>\n\n====2007\u201308 season====\nBridge played his third cup final for Chelsea in just over two years in the 2\u20131 loss in the [[2008 Football League Cup Final|2008 League Cup Final]] against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. Bridge was adjudged to have handled the ball in the penalty area and Tottenham were awarded a penalty from which they scored, going on to win 2\u20131 after extra-time.\n\n====2008\u201309 season====\nIn the League Cup fourth round tie against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in the [[2008\u201309 Chelsea F.C. season|2008\u201309 season]], Bridge wore the captain's armband in the absence of [[John Terry]] and [[Frank Lampard]], but the Blues lost on penalties.\n\n===Manchester City===\n====2009\u201311====\n[[File:London pixel city.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Bridge refuses to shake [[John Terry]]'s hand at the start of Manchester City's game against Chelsea on 27 February 2010.]]\nOn 2 January 2009, it was confirmed by [[Mark Hughes]] that [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] had agreed an undisclosed fee with Chelsea for Bridge, thought to be around \u00a310&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_city/7807951.stm |title=Bridge seals transfer to Man City |publisher=BBC Sport   |date =3 January 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 }}</ref> and, on the following day, Manchester City agreed personal terms with the player, who later passed his medical, thus enabling the transfer to be completed and he signed a four-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Club-news/2009/January/Wayne-Bridge-signs-for-Manchester-City |title=Wayne Bridge signs for Manchester City |publisher=Manchester City |date =3 January 2009 |accessdate=8 December 2009 }}</ref> Bridge was unveiled to the home fans that day at an FA Cup home tie against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], and two weeks later made his debut for the club in a 1\u20130 win against [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in the league. He was given the squad number 25. For the [[2009\u201310 Manchester City F.C. season|2009\u201310 season]], Bridge switched to the number 3, which was previously worn by [[Michael Ball (footballer)|Michael Ball]].\n\nOn 27 February 2010, City inflicted Chelsea's first home Premier League defeat of the [[2009\u201310 Premier League|season]] with a 4\u20132 victory. Prior to the match, Bridge was involved in a highly publicised incident in which he refused to shake hands with Chelsea captain and former club and international teammate [[John Terry]], who was at the time the subject of claims<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2010/oct/07/newsoftheworld-john-terry \"Two newspapers apologise to Vanessa Perroncel for breaching her privacy\"], [[Roy Greenslade]], [[The Guardian|The Guardian (Online)]], 7 October 2010</ref> that he had had an affair with Bridge's ex-girlfriend Vanessa Perroncel.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/feb/27/john-terry-wayne-bridge Wayne Bridge v John Terry \u2013 how it unfolded], Scott Murray, The Guardian (Online), 27 February 2010</ref> His position as left-back for Manchester City gradually faded with the arrival of two new left-backs. In the summer of 2010, Manchester City manager [[Roberto Mancini]] signed [[Aleksandar Kolarov]] from [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], and in 2011 signed [[Ga\u00ebl Clichy]] from Arsenal, thus indicating Bridge was surplus to requirements at City.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini hopes Wayne Bridge will leave Man City in January |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16280364 |work=BBC Sport |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=2 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n====West Ham loan====\n[[File:WayneBridge2011.jpg|90px|thumb|right|Bridge playing for [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]].]]\nOn 12 January 2011, Bridge joined [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bridge delighted to sign |url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20110112/bridge-delighted-to-sign_2236884_2264968 |publisher=West Ham United FC |accessdate=12 January 2011 |date=12 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114202243/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20110112/bridge-delighted-to-sign_2236884_2264968 |archivedate=14 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> He made his West Ham debut on 15 January 2011 in a 3\u20130 loss to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Darling |first=Kevin |title=West Ham 0\u20133 Arsenal|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9359364.stm|work=Arsenal brush aside poor Hammers |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=16 January 2011|date=15 January 2011}}</ref>\nBridge made 18 appearances in all competitions for West Ham before his loan ended.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|15061|2010|accessdate=2015-08-15}}</ref>\n\n====Sunderland loan====\nOn 31 January 2012, it was announced that Bridge had joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on a loan deal until the end of the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/20120131/oneill-ties-up-bridge-deal_2256213_2595013|title=O'Neill ties up Bridge deal|date=31 January 2012|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|accessdate=31 January 2012}}</ref> He made his debut appearance as an 82nd minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Kieran Richardson]] in Sunderland's 3\u20130 victory over [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] the following day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunderland 3 \u2013 0 Norwich City|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16714048|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 February 2012}}</ref> He made his first start for Sunderland in their 1\u20130 win over Liverpool on 10 March 2012, and also featured in the FA Cup quarter-final draw with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] the following week.\n\n====Brighton loan====\nOn 6 July 2012, it was confirmed that Bridge would join [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wayne Bridge joins Brighton from Man City on a season-long loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18740583|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 July 2012}}</ref> He made his debut for Brighton on 14 August 2012 in a 3\u20130 away defeat to [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]].<ref name=\"bhdebut\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19159798 | title=Swindon 3\u20130 Brighton | publisher=BBC Sport | date=14 August 2012 | accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> His first Brighton goal came on 25 August 2012 in a 5\u20131 home victory over [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]], his first league goal since scoring for Chelsea in December 2003.\n<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19304109 | title=Brighton 5\u20131 Barnsley | publisher=BBC Sport | date=25 August 2012 | accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> Bridge played 37 league games for Brighton, scoring three goals and helping them reach fourth place in [[EFL Championship|the league]] to qualify for the [[Football League play-offs|play-offs]]. He played in both semi-final games against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] where Brighton were beaten 2\u20130 on aggregate.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|15061|2012|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22424087 | title=Brighton 0\u20132 Crystal Palace | publisher=BBC Sport | date=13 May 2013| accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> At the end of the season, Bridge thanked Brighton manager [[Gus Poyet]] for revitalising his footballing career. He told ''[[The Independent]]'', \"Brighton have been great to me. I just want to say a big thank you to the chairman and the fans. Gus has revitalised my love for football after I was in the wilderness at Manchester City.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/wayne-bridge-praises-brightons-underfire-manager-gus-poyets-prowess-8623045.html | title=Wayne Bridge praises Brighton's under-fire manager Gus Poyet's prowess |work=The Independent | date=20 May 2013 | accessdate=27 May 2013 | last=Wallace |first=Aam |}}</ref>\n\n===Reading===\nIn June 2013, Bridge signed a one-year contract with [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], who had just been relegated to the [[Football League Championship]]. Bridge chose Reading ahead of offers from [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] and Brighton, who wished to make his loan permanent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/queens-park-rangers/10105012/Harry-Redknapp-left-furious-after-Queens-Park-Rangers-bid-for-free-agent-Wayne-Bridge-is-hijacked-by-Reading.html|title=Harry Redknapp left furious after Queens Park Rangers' bid for free agent Wayne Bridge is hijacked by Reading|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=7 June 2013 |first=John|last=Percy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/bridge-to-sign-for-the-royals-070613-857575.aspx|title=Bridge to sign for the Royals|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=7 June 2013 |accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 May 2014, Bridge was released by Reading after 12 games in his only season for the club, subsequently retiring from professional football.<ref name=\"5 released\">{{cite web |title=Jobi, Mikele & Kaspars to move on|url=http://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/article/mcanuff-leigertwood-gorkss-leave-060514-1539505.aspx|publisher=Reading F.C.|date=6 May 2014 |accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Bridge Retires\">{{cite web|title=Wayne Bridge: Ex-England left-back announces retirement |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27302154|publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 May 2014 |accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nDuring his time with Southampton, all Bridge's managers ([[Dave Jones (football manager)|Jones]], [[Glenn Hoddle|Hoddle]] and [[Stuart Gray (footballer, born 1960)|Gray]]) predicted full international honours.<ref name=ITN/> He was soon making regular appearances for the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 team]], and the managers' prophecy was realised when [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] gave him his first full cap against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] on 13 February 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandstats.com/matchreport.php?mid=786 |title=Holland 1 \u2013 England 1 (match summary) |publisher=englandstats.com |accessdate=8 September 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/Players/Postings/2004/03/Wayne+Bridge+Chelsea.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20071029052657/http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/Players/Postings/2004/03/Wayne+Bridge+Chelsea.htm |url-status=dead |archivedate=29 October 2007 |title=Wayne Bridge, Fulham |publisher=TheFA.com |accessdate=6 September 2007}}</ref> He quickly proved himself and appeared twice as a substitute in the [[Football World Cup 2002|2002 World Cup]], although he did not appear at all in [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]], with [[Ashley Cole]] being preferred.\n\nDuring qualification for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], Bridge occupied England's problematic left midfield position, but lost this to his Chelsea teammate [[Joe Cole]] when he received an injury. He returned to the England team for a friendly against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] in November 2005, covering for the injured Cole at left back and winning his 21st cap.\n\nBridge played in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying|Euro 2008 qualifier]] match against [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 6 June 2007, which England won 3\u20130, with Bridge assisting Joe Cole's goal with a long throw into the box.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/6716859.stm |title=Estonia 0\u20133 England |publisher=BBC  |accessdate=8 September 2007 | date=6 June 2007 |first=Phil |last=McNulty}}</ref>\n\nBridge's final appearance for England was against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] on 14 November 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englandstats.com/matchreport.php?mid=881|title=England 0 \u2013 Brazil 1 (14th November 2009)|publisher=englandstats.com|accessdate=28 February 2010}}</ref>\nOn 25 February 2010, Bridge announced his permanent withdrawal from international duty following allegations regarding England captain [[John Terry]] and Bridge's former girlfriend Vanessa Perroncel.<ref name = \"Its over\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8536491.stm |title=England's Wayne Bridge withdraws from internationals |publisher=BBC  |accessdate=25 February 2010 | date=25 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Wayne Bridge and son.jpg|thumb|120px|Bridge with his son Jaydon.]]\nBridge was in a relationship with French model Vanessa Perroncel from 2005 to 2009. They had a son together, Jaydon Jean Claude Bridge, who was born on 21 November 2006. The next day, Bridge signed a new four-year contract with Chelsea, on 22 November 2006.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/6178676.stm |title=Bridge signs new Chelsea contract |publisher=BBC Sport  |accessdate=6 September 2007 | date=23 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, a [[Injunction#Super-injunction|super injunction]] was imposed by a [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|High Court judge]] preventing the media reporting that Bridge's former teammate [[John Terry]] had allegedly had an affair with Perroncel shortly after she split from Bridge. The injunction was lifted a week later.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/7102733/Judge-lifts-super-injunction-over-John-Terry-affair-with-team-mates-girlfriend.html |title=Judge lifts super injunction over John Terry affair with team-mate's girlfriend|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |first1=Gordon|last1= Rayner |first2= Martin |last2=Evans |date=29 January 2010 |accessdate=29 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8488232.stm|title=John Terry gagging order lifted by High Court |date=29 January 2010|work=BBC Sport |accessdate=29 January 2010}}</ref> On 25 March, Perroncel succeeded in a claim against Bridge for maintenance for their son with the High Court awarding her a payment of \u00a36,000 per month until Jaydon's 18th birthday.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/03/27/wayne-bridge-ordered-to-pay-ex-vanessa-perroncell-1million-115875-22141253/|title=Wayne Bridge ordered to pay ex Vanessa Perroncell \u00a31million |date=27 March 2010|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> The ''[[News of the World]]'' printed an apology for the story on 3 October 2010 to Perroncel for invading her private life, and indicating that she has refuted the claims against herself and Terry.<ref>{{cite news|last=Greenslade|first=Roy|title=Two newspapers apologise to Vanessa Perroncel for breaching her privacy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2010/oct/07/newsoftheworld-john-terry|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=28 November 2010|date=7 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2013, [[The Saturdays]] singer [[Frankie Sandford]] announced on Twitter that she was engaged to Bridge. She gave birth to their son, Parker Bridge, on 18 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/24578265 | title=The Saturdays star Frankie Sandford gives birth to son | publisher=BBC Newsbeat | date=18 October 2013 | accessdate=19 March 2014 | author=Butterly, Amelia}}</ref> The couple married on 19 July 2014 in a private ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|first=Dominic|last= Harris |url=https://www.thevow.ie/saturdays-star-frankie-sandford-and-wayne-bridge-get-married-30445069.html |title=Saturdays star Frankie Sandford and Wayne Bridge get married |work= The Vow |date=20 July 2014  |accessdate=15 August 2015 }}</ref> In January 2015, Sandford announced that they were expecting their second child. On 15 August 2015, Carter Bridge was born.<ref>{{cite news |last=Longmire |first=Becca |url=http://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/598569/Frankie-Bridge-husband-Wayne-welcome-baby-son-Carter |title=It's a boy: Frankie Bridge and husband Wayne welcome 'gorgeous' baby son Carter |work=The Express  |date=15 August 2015 |accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nBridge was a contestant in the [[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK series 16)|2016 series]] of TV show  ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK TV series)|I'm a Celebrity... Get Me Out of Here!]]'', but was voted out on 2 December.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blumson |first1=Amy|title=I'm A Celebrity 2016: final four  prepare to take on Celebrity Cyclone trial|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/12/01/celebrity-get-martin-grates-carol-leaves-camp-plus-scarlett/|accessdate=3 December 2016|work=Daily Telegraph|date=3 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Wayne Bridge ejected from I'm A Celebrity... Get Me Out Of Here! |url=http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/14944827.Wayne_Bridge_ejected_from_I_m_A_Celebrity____Get_Me_Out_Of_Here_/ |accessdate=3 December 2016|work=Daily Echo |location= Southampton |date=3 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nBridge has spoken about his love for playing poker, which began when his friends started a local monthly home game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wayne Bridge opens up about Brighton card school |url=https://calvinayre.com/2017/04/25/poker/wayne-bridge-opens-brighton-card-school-pokerstars-interview-video/ |first=Lee |last=Davy |accessdate=30 March 2018|website=[[Calvin Ayre|CalvinAyre.com]]|date=25 April 2017}}</ref> Bridge plays in one day live events, and has described his style of play as 'kamikaze'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wayne Bridge Exclusive: Jose Mourinho remaining positive in crisis |url=https://www.888poker.com/magazine/poker-world/888poker-headsup-Wayne-Bridge |first=Chad |last=Holloway |accessdate=30 March 2018 |publisher=[[888poker]]|date=1 January 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Wayne Bridge |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=15061 |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n! Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=6|[[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]\n| [[1998\u201399 Southampton F.C. season|1998\u201399]]\n|[[Premier League]]\n| 23||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014\n| 24||0\n|-\n| [[1999\u20132000 Southampton F.C. season|1999\u20132000]]\n|Premier League\n| 18||1||2||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014\n| 22||1\n|-\n| [[2000\u201301 Southampton F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n|Premier League\n| 38||0||4||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014\n| 45||0\n|-\n| [[2001\u201302 Southampton F.C. season|2001\u201302]]\n|Premier League\n| 38||0||1||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014\n| 42||0\n|-\n| [[2002\u201303 Southampton F.C. season|2002\u201303]]\n|Premier League\n| 34||1||4||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014\n| 40||1\n|-\n! colspan=2|Total\n! 151||2||11||0||11||0||colspan=2|\u2014\n! 173||2\n|-\n| rowspan=7|[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]\n| [[2003\u201304 C