{"title_page": "Emily Burns", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = \n| name             = Emily Burns\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1994|09|22}}\n| origin           = [[Rugby, Warwickshire]]\n| genre            = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| occupation       = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://emilyburnsmusic.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Emily Burns''' *also goes by Eminem Burns the 6 foot Spanish singer) (born 22 September 1994) is a [[singer-songwriter]] originally from [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]], England, now based in [[London]]. Her music style is influenced by artists such as [[Tove Lo]], [[Kehlani]], [[Sigrid (singer)|Sigrid]] and [[Banks (singer)|Banks]].\n\n== Career ==\n\nBurns entered the [[Live and Unsigned]] competition in 2010, reaching the final to perform at the [[indig02]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://breakingmorewaves.blogspot.co.uk/2013/06/emily-burns.html|title=Emily Burns - New Waves|website=breakingmorewaves.blogspot.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>  She was subsequently invited to attended a [[masterclass]] at [[Abbey Road Studios]], where inhouse producer Rob Cass signed Burns to Cave Productions, leading to the release of the single \"Plasters, Glitter and Glue\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/underdogs/emily-burns-is-one-to-watch/|title=Emily Burns is one to watch|date=August 6, 2013|first=Pip|last=Ellwood-Hughes|work=Entertainment Focus|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-18190523|title=Burns on track for music career|date=2012-05-24|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nShe performed at numerous festivals, including a tour of the [[Czech Republic]] and appearances on two different stages at the Secret Garden Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glasswerk.co.uk/magazine/article/18902/Introducing+Emily+Burns/|title=Introducing Emily Burns|first=Gordon|last=Johnston|website=Glasswerk Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502212744/http://glasswerk.co.uk/magazine/article/18902/Introducing+Emily+Burns/|archive-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> Emily also had a slot on the [[BBC introducing]] stage at [[T in the Park]] in July 2013, which led to \"Plasters, Glitter and Glue\" being play listed on [[BBC Radio 1]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/introducing/entries/941ed49e-61b2-3e75-a933-e1c88f4e7bd6|title=On the playlist: Emily Burns - Plasters, Glitter and Glue|date=2013-08-06|website=BBC Music Introducing|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref> Burns also performed on [[SB.TV]] and [[Mahogany Sessions]] in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.recordoftheday.com/on-the-move/record/emily-burns/take-it-or-leave-it|title=Record of the Day - In tune. Informed. Indispensable|website=www.recordoftheday.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n\nBurns started working as a receptionist at [[Abbey Road Studios]] in 2014, which led to meeting producer Sound Of Fractures, who produced her first major single \"Take It Or Leave It\", which was released in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/abbey-road-receptionist-launches-bid-for-stardom-a3404966.html|title=Abbey Road receptionist launches bid for stardom|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBurns signed to [[record label]] 37 Adventures in July 2017 and released her first single with the label, \"Bitch\", in January 2018 followed by her second single, \"Girlfriend At The Time\", in March 2018.<ref>https://37adventures.bandcamp.com/track/bitch</ref> Burns released her first [[extended play|EP]], ''Seven Scenes From The Same Summer'', in July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://37adventures.bandcamp.com/album/seven-scenes-from-the-same-summer|title=Seven Scenes From The Same Summer, by Emily Burns|website=37 Adventures|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.media-match.com/uk/music/article/review/emily-burns-girlfriend-at-the-time|title=EMILY BURNS - Girlfriend At The Time|work=UK Music Match|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!<br />\n\n==== Title ====\n<br />\n!\n==== Album Details ====\n|-\n|Seven Scenes from the Same Summer <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Seven-Scenes-Same-Summer-Explicit/dp/B07HDBLWH3/ref=sr_1_2?keywords=emily+burns&qid=1572632525&sr=8-2|title=Seven Scenes from the Same Summer [Explicit] by Emily Burns on Amazon Music - Amazon.co.uk|website=www.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: 25 July 2018\n* Label: 37 Adventures\n* Format: Digital Download\n\n<br />\n|}\n\n=== EPs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Title\n<br />\n!Album Details\n<br />\n|-\n|PDA <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/PDA-Explicit-Emily-Burns/dp/B07SF7PHNS/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=emily+burns&qid=1572633585&sr=8-1|title=PDA [Explicit] by Emily Burns on Amazon Music - Amazon.co.uk|website=www.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: 19 June 2019\n* Label: Emily Burns\n* Format: Digital Download\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/emilyburnsuk/ Emily Burns] on [[Facebook]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burns, Emily}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby High School for Girls]]\n[[Category:People from Rugby, Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n\n\n{{singer-songwriter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = \n| name             = Emily Burns\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1994|09|22}}\n| origin           = [[Rugby, Warwickshire]]\n| genre            = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| occupation       = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://emilyburnsmusic.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''Emily Burns''' (born 22 September 1994) is a [[singer-songwriter]] originally from [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]], England, now based in [[London]]. Her music style is influenced by artists such as [[Tove Lo]], [[Kehlani]], [[Sigrid (singer)|Sigrid]] and [[Banks (singer)|Banks]].\n\n== Career ==\n\nBurns entered the [[Live and Unsigned]] competition in 2010, reaching the final to perform at the [[indig02]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://breakingmorewaves.blogspot.co.uk/2013/06/emily-burns.html|title=Emily Burns - New Waves|website=breakingmorewaves.blogspot.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>  She was subsequently invited to attended a [[masterclass]] at [[Abbey Road Studios]], where inhouse producer Rob Cass signed Burns to Cave Productions, leading to the release of the single \"Plasters, Glitter and Glue\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/underdogs/emily-burns-is-one-to-watch/|title=Emily Burns is one to watch|date=August 6, 2013|first=Pip|last=Ellwood-Hughes|work=Entertainment Focus|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-18190523|title=Burns on track for music career|date=2012-05-24|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nShe performed at numerous festivals, including a tour of the [[Czech Republic]] and appearances on two different stages at the Secret Garden Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glasswerk.co.uk/magazine/article/18902/Introducing+Emily+Burns/|title=Introducing Emily Burns|first=Gordon|last=Johnston|website=Glasswerk Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502212744/http://glasswerk.co.uk/magazine/article/18902/Introducing+Emily+Burns/|archive-date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> Emily also had a slot on the [[BBC introducing]] stage at [[T in the Park]] in July 2013, which led to \"Plasters, Glitter and Glue\" being play listed on [[BBC Radio 1]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/introducing/entries/941ed49e-61b2-3e75-a933-e1c88f4e7bd6|title=On the playlist: Emily Burns - Plasters, Glitter and Glue|date=2013-08-06|website=BBC Music Introducing|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref> Burns also performed on [[SB.TV]] and [[Mahogany Sessions]] in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.recordoftheday.com/on-the-move/record/emily-burns/take-it-or-leave-it|title=Record of the Day - In tune. Informed. Indispensable|website=www.recordoftheday.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref>\n\nBurns started working as a receptionist at [[Abbey Road Studios]] in 2014, which led to meeting producer Sound Of Fractures, who produced her first major single \"Take It Or Leave It\", which was released in November 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/abbey-road-receptionist-launches-bid-for-stardom-a3404966.html|title=Abbey Road receptionist launches bid for stardom|work=Evening Standard|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBurns signed to [[record label]] 37 Adventures in July 2017 and released her first single with the label, \"Bitch\", in January 2018 followed by her second single, \"Girlfriend At The Time\", in March 2018.<ref>https://37adventures.bandcamp.com/track/bitch</ref> Burns released her first [[extended play|EP]], ''Seven Scenes From The Same Summer'', in July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://37adventures.bandcamp.com/album/seven-scenes-from-the-same-summer|title=Seven Scenes From The Same Summer, by Emily Burns|website=37 Adventures|access-date=2018-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.media-match.com/uk/music/article/review/emily-burns-girlfriend-at-the-time|title=EMILY BURNS - Girlfriend At The Time|work=UK Music Match|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!<br />\n\n==== Title ====\n<br />\n!\n==== Album Details ====\n|-\n|Seven Scenes from the Same Summer <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Seven-Scenes-Same-Summer-Explicit/dp/B07HDBLWH3/ref=sr_1_2?keywords=emily+burns&qid=1572632525&sr=8-2|title=Seven Scenes from the Same Summer [Explicit] by Emily Burns on Amazon Music - Amazon.co.uk|website=www.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: 25 July 2018\n* Label: 37 Adventures\n* Format: Digital Download\n\n<br />\n|}\n\n=== EPs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Title\n<br />\n!Album Details\n<br />\n|-\n|PDA <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/PDA-Explicit-Emily-Burns/dp/B07SF7PHNS/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=emily+burns&qid=1572633585&sr=8-1|title=PDA [Explicit] by Emily Burns on Amazon Music - Amazon.co.uk|website=www.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: 19 June 2019\n* Label: Emily Burns\n* Format: Digital Download\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/emilyburnsuk/ Emily Burns] on [[Facebook]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burns, Emily}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby High School for Girls]]\n[[Category:People from Rugby, Warwickshire]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n\n\n{{singer-songwriter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Eminemburnss", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emily_Burns"}
{"title_page": "Naval Base Impalila", "text_new": "{{Infobox military installation\n|name= Naval Base Impalila\n|ensign= \n|native_name= \n|partof= <!-- for elements within a larger site -->\n|location= \n|nearest_town= [[Katima Mulilo]]<!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n|country= {{NAM}}\n|image= \n|caption= \n|pushpin_map= \n|pushpin_label_position= \n|pushpin_mapsize= \n|pushpin_map_caption= \n|coordinates= \n|type= [[Naval base]]\n|site_area= <!-- area of site m2, km2 square mile etc -->\n|height= <!-- height of tallest part, not above sea level -->\n|ownership= [[Ministry of Defence (Namibia)]]<!--government department such as the MoD or the United States DoD-->\n|operator= [[Namibian Navy]] <!--where different from ownership such as the RAF or the USAF-->\n|controlledby= [[Namibian Defence Force]] <!--such as RAF Bomber Command or the Eighth Air Force-->\n|open_to_public= <!--for out of use sites/sites with museums etc-->\n|condition= Active\n|built= <!-- {{Start date|YYYY}} -->\n|builder= \n|used= <!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n|materials= \n|fate= <!--changed from demolished parameter-->\n|battles= \n|events= \n|current_commander= Commander Christian Keendjele\n|past_commanders= <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n|garrison= <!-- such as the 25th Bombardment Group -->\n|occupants= <!-- squadrons only -->\n|TC= \n|LID= \n|GPS= \n|WMO= \n|website= \n|footnotes= \n}}\n'''Naval Base Impalila''' is a riverine base of the Namibian Navy.It is located on Impalila Island\n==History==\nThe base was orginally contructed by the [[South African Defence Force]] and used by the [[South African Marine Corps]]. It was abandoned in 1989 during South Africa's withdrawal from Namibia. After Namibia's independence it was used as a secondary school<ref>https://www.defenceweb.co.za/security/maritime-security/namibia-commissions-new-naval-facility/</ref>.IN 2011 the navy condcuted a Navy Coastal-land, Riverine and Meteorological survey, which found critical security gaps<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/impalila-naval-base-officially-opened</ref>. The report led to the creation of the naval district covering [[Zambezi]], [[Chobe]] and [[Okavango]] rivers. Rehabilitation of the base began in 2014 and was completed in 2017.\n\n==Current Status==\nThe base was commissioned into service by the Minister of Defence Penda ya Ndakolo on 21 June 2019<ref>https://www.nampa.org/index.php?model=featured&function=display&id=152748</ref>. A Marine Operational Boat Team is based at the base and conducts [[riverine]] patrols<ref>https://www.nbc.na/news/minister-defence-inaugurates-impalila-island-naval-base.21271</ref>.\n\n==Commanding officers==\n21 June 2019- Incubent Commander Christian Keendjele<ref>https://www.namibian.com.na/189893/archive-read/Impalila-naval-base-commissioned</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in Namibia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military installation\n|name= Naval Base Impalila\n|ensign= \n|native_name= \n|partof= <!-- for elements within a larger site -->\n|location= \n|nearest_town= [[Katima Mulilo]]<!-- used in military test site infobox -->\n|country= {{NAM}}\n|image= \n|caption= \n|pushpin_map= \n|pushpin_label_position= \n|pushpin_mapsize= \n|pushpin_map_caption= \n|coordinates= \n|type= [[Naval base]]\n|site_area= <!-- area of site m2, km2 square mile etc -->\n|height= <!-- height of tallest part, not above sea level -->\n|ownership= [[Ministry of Defence (Namibia)]]<!--government department such as the MoD or the United States DoD-->\n|operator= [[Namibian Navy]] <!--where different from ownership such as the RAF or the USAF-->\n|controlledby= [[Namibian Defence Force]] <!--such as RAF Bomber Command or the Eighth Air Force-->\n|open_to_public= <!--for out of use sites/sites with museums etc-->\n|condition= Active\n|built= <!-- {{Start date|YYYY}} -->\n|builder= \n|used= <!--{{End date|1946}} -->\n|materials= \n|fate= <!--changed from demolished parameter-->\n|battles= \n|events= \n|current_commander= Commander Christian Keendjele\n|past_commanders= <!-- past notable commander(s) -->\n|garrison= <!-- such as the 25th Bombardment Group -->\n|occupants= <!-- squadrons only -->\n|TC= \n|LID= \n|GPS= \n|WMO= \n|website= \n|footnotes= \n}}\n'''Naval Base Impalila''' is a riverine base of the Namibian Navy.It is located on Impalila Island\n==History==\nThe base was orginally contructed by the [[South African Defence Force]] and used by the [[South African Marine Corps]]. It was abandoned in 1989 during South Africa's withdrawal from Namibia. After Namibia's independence it was used as a secondary school<ref>https://www.defenceweb.co.za/security/maritime-security/namibia-commissions-new-naval-facility/</ref>.IN 2011 the navy condcuted a Navy Coastal-land, Riverine and Meteorological survey, which found critical security gaps<ref>https://neweralive.na/posts/impalila-naval-base-officially-opened</ref>. The report led to the creation of the naval district covering [[Zambezi]], [[Chobe]] and [[Okavango]] rivers. Rehabilitation of the base began in 2014 and was completed in 2017.\n\n==Current Status==\nThe base was commissioned into service by the Minister of Defence Penda ya Ndakolo on 21 June 2019<ref>https://www.nampa.org/index.php?model=featured&function=display&id=152748</ref>. A Marine Operational Boat Team is based at the base and conducts riverine patrols<ref>https://www.nbc.na/news/minister-defence-inaugurates-impalila-island-naval-base.21271</ref>.\n\n==Commanding officers==\n21 June 2019- Incubent Commander Christian Keendjele<ref>https://www.namibian.com.na/189893/archive-read/Impalila-naval-base-commissioned</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n[[Category:2019 establishments in Namibia]]\n", "name_user": "ViceAdmiral", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent Status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naval_Base_Impalila"}
{"title_page": "Jim Baxter", "text_new": "{{for|the Australian rules footballer|Jim Baxter (Australian footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image          = Jim Baxter in Scotland shirt.png\n| caption        = Baxter during his time at [[Nottingham Forest]]\n| fullname       = James Curran Baxter<ref>{{Hugman|1167|accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1939|9|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Hill of Beath]], [[Fife]], Scotland\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|2001|4|14|1939|9|29|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Glasgow]], Scotland<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1179640.stm |title=Rangers legend Baxter dies |work=BBC Sport |date=14 April 2001 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> \n| position       = [[Wing half|Left-half]]\n| youthyears1    = \n| youthclubs1    = Halbeath Juveniles\n| youthyears2    = \n| youthclubs2    = [[Crossgates Primrose J.F.C.|Crossgates Primrose]]\n| years1         = 1957\u20131960\n| years2         = 1960\u20131965\n| years3         = 1965\u20131967\n| years4         = 1967\n| years5         = 1967\u20131969\n| years6         = 1969\u20131970\n| clubs1         = [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n| clubs2         = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| clubs3         = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| clubs4         = \u2192 [[Vancouver Royals|Vancouver Royal Canadians]] (loan)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasljerseys.com/Players/B/Baxter.Jim.htm |work=North American Soccer League Players |title=NASL profile - Jim Baxter |accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n| clubs5         = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| clubs6         = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps1          = 62\n| goals1         = 3\n| caps2          = 136\n| goals2         = 18\n| caps3          = 87\n| goals3         = 10\n| caps4          = 12\n| goals4         = 2\n| caps5          = 48\n| goals5         = 3\n| caps6          = 14\n| goals6         = 1\n| totalcaps      = 359\n| totalgoals     = 37\n| nationalyears1 = 1958<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu23/player.php?playerid=52|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Scotland Under-23|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scotland national under-23 football team|Scotland Under-23]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1960<ref name=scot60s>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lITgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT215&lpg=PT215&dq=1964+%22scotland+XI%22+v+%22scottish+league%22&source=bl&ots=DjEqsyzxpo&sig=ACfU3U1by2fCMyV966wejpqXzOUTR3RFdw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjU-d_FrZ_jAhVmRRUIHVsBCm4Q6AEwCXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22scotland%20XI%22%20v%20%22scottish%20league%22&f=false|title=Scotland in the 60s: The Definitive Account of the Scottish National Football Side During the 1960s|author=Ronnie McDevitt|year=2016|publisher=Pitch Publishing|isbn=9781785312458}}</ref>\n| nationalteam2  = [[List of Scottish Football League representative players#Scotland trial matches / SFL Centenary players|SFL trial v SFA]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1960\u20131967\n| nationalteam3  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 34\n| nationalgoals3 = 3\n| nationalyears4 = 1961\u20131964<ref name=scot60s/>\n| nationalteam4  = [[List of Scottish Football League representative players#Scotland trial matches / SFL Centenary players|SFA trial v SFL]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 2\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 1961\u20131964<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/jamescurranbaxter.html|title=Matches played by James Curran Baxter for Scottish Football League XI|publisher=London Hearts Supporters Club |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n| nationalteam5  = [[Scottish Football League XI|Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps5  = 5\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n}}\n\n'''James Curran Baxter''' (29 September 1939 \u2013 14 April 2001) was a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[wing half|left half]]. He is generally regarded as one of the country's greatest ever players. He was born, educated and started his career in [[Fife]], but his peak playing years were in the early 1960s with the [[Glasgow]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], whom he helped to win ten trophies between 1960 and 1965, and where he became known as \"Slim Jim\". However, he started drinking heavily during a four-month layoff caused by a leg fracture in December 1964, his fitness suffered, and he was [[Transfer (football)|transferred]] to [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in summer 1965. In two and a half years at Sunderland he played 98 games and scored 12 goals, becoming known for drinking himself unconscious the night before a match and playing well the next day. At the end of 1967 Sunderland transferred him to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], who gave him a [[Free transfer (football)|free transfer]] back to Rangers in 1969 after 50 games. After a further year with Rangers Baxter retired from football in 1970, at the age of 31.\n\nFrom 1960 to 1967, he was a leading member of a strong Scottish international team that lost only once to [[England national football team|England]], in 1965, shortly after he recovered from the leg fracture. He thought his best international performance was a 2\u20131 win against England in 1963, when he scored both goals after Scotland were reduced to 10 players. In the 1967 match against England, who had won the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 World Cup]], he taunted the opposition by ball juggling while waiting for his teammates to find good positions. Although he was given most of the credit for the 3\u20132 win, some commentators wished he had made an effort to run up a bigger score.\n\nIn his prime, Baxter was known for his ability to raise a team's morale, his good tactical vision, precise passing and ability to send opponents the wrong way \u2013 and for being a joker on the pitch. He also broke with Glasgow tradition by becoming friendly with several members of their major [[Old Firm|Glasgow rivals]], [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].\n\nAlthough he gained a reputation as a womaniser when he moved to Glasgow, he married in 1965 and had two sons. The marriage broke up in 1981, and in 1983 he formed another relationship that lasted the rest of his life. After retiring from football he became manager of a [[Public house|pub]], and his continued heavy drinking damaged his liver so badly that he needed two [[Organ transplant|transplant]]s at the age of 55, after which he swore off [[Alcoholic beverage|alcohol]]. Baxter was also addicted to gambling, and is estimated to have lost between \u00a3250,000 and \u00a3500,000. After he died of [[pancreatic cancer]] in 2001, his funeral was held in [[Glasgow Cathedral]] and his ashes were buried at Rangers' [[Ibrox Stadium]]. In 2003, a statue was erected in his honour at his hometown, [[Hill of Beath]].\n\n==Early life==\nBaxter was born in [[Hill of Beath]], [[Fife]], on 29 September 1939 and was educated and started his career there. After leaving school he spent eight months as an apprentice [[Cabinet making|cabinet maker]], and then worked as a coal miner.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" />\n\nHis former headmaster James Carmichael took an interest in ex-pupils and encouraged Baxter to join local football team Halbeath Juveniles instead of one of the glamour clubs.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> Baxter went on to play for the Fife junior team, [[Crossgates Primrose J.F.C.|Crossgates Primrose]].<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" />\n\n==Club career==\n===Raith Rovers===\nBaxter joined [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] as a part-timer in 1957.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> In his time at Raith he orchestrated a 3-2 win over Rangers at Ibrox. [[Scot Symon]] decided he wanted to sign him for Rangers from that performance.\n\nIn an interview on his career, Baxter was asked if joining the senior ranks was the beginning of his football education. He said he found the idea of being given any sort of football education laughable, before then commenting on [[Willie McNaught]]. Describing McNaught as, 'a smashing guy', Baxter explained how instead of thoughtlessly charging forward with the ball, McNaught suggested more considered football \u2013 change from running 30 yards to produce a five-yard pass to running five yards and producing a 30-yard pass. This, Baxter then stated, was his football education with Willie McNaught the provider.<ref name = \"qoswillie\">{{cite web |url=http://www.qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=1215 |title=Willie McNaught (and Ken) |work=Queen of the South official website |date=26 April 2012 |accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref> He later said of his time with the two Fife clubs, \"I would never have made it in today's circumstances. I needed bastards like Carmichael, Buckard, Ferrier, [[Bert Herdman|Herdman]] and McNaught. Young players like I was would simply tell them to get stuffed and take their talent elsewhere. I owe them.\"<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" />\n\n===Rangers===\nIn June 1960,<ref name=\"UEFABaxter\">{{cite web|title=On This Day: 29 September |publisher=[[UEFA]] |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/history/OnThisDay/index,newsid=216506.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209071201/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/history/onthisday/index%2Cnewsid%3D216506.html |archivedate= 9 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> he joined the [[Glasgow]] team [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] for a [[transfer fee]] of \u00a317,500, a Scottish record at the time.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\"/><!--\nhttp://www.uefa.com/uefa/history/OnThisDay/index,newsid=216506.html not on Internet Archive on 24 September 2010, try again in Mar 2011\n-->\n\nBaxter played for Rangers from 1960 to 1965, mainly as an attacking [[left half]]. During this period the team won the [[Scottish Football League Premier Division|Scottish League]] Championship in 1961, 1963 and 1964,<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> and were winners of three [[Scottish Cup]]s and four [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]s from as many finals, Baxter playing in all seven ties.<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\" /> Rangers fans remember him as \"Slim Jim\", and in 18 \"[[Old Firm]]\" games against local rivals [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] \u2013 ten Scottish League, five League Cup and three Scottish Cup matches \u2013 he was only twice on the losing side.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /> His first Rangers game was in August 1960 at [[inside left]] against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in the Scottish League Cup. He scored his first goal for the club in November 1960, against [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]],<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> and in the same month scored an early goal in Rangers' 8\u20130 win over the German team [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]].<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> In [[1961 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1961]] Baxter played in the Rangers team that contested the first ever [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] Final, a [[two-legged tie]] that they lost 4\u20131 on aggregate to [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref name=\"RSSSF ECWC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec196061.html#cwc |title=Cup Winners' Cup 1960-61 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |accessdate=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n \nIn December 1964, Baxter played brilliantly to set up a 2\u20130 win for Rangers in an away game against [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Vienna]] in the [[1964\u201365 European Cup|European Cup]]. With the game won, rather than play out time Baxter's confidence over-extended into arrogance to make fun of his opponents with the ball. In the last minute he went to 'nutmeg' an opponent, who was having none of it and broke Baxter's leg with his challenge.<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\" /> This was to be a watershed for Baxter. During the four months in which he was unable to play he began drinking to his detriment; this ultimately was to curtail his playing career and his life.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" />\n\n===Sunderland===\nBaxter joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] for a [[transfer fee]] of \u00a372,500, the highest ever paid to a Scottish club at the time.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /><ref name=\"IndependentSelfconfidentMaster\" /> Baxter played 98 games for Sunderland in England's First Division (then the top tier), scoring 12 goals.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\">{{cite book |title=Black Catalogue: We are Sunderland |editor=Ken Gambles |publisher=PDG Books Ltd |year=2005 |isbn=1-905519-02-8 |last=Robson |first=Barry |chapter=The One and Only, Slim Jim |pages=1\u20134 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7t2rTXPLs-oC&pg=PA3&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPA1,M1 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianObit\" />\n\n===Nottingham Forest===\nIn December 1967, English First Division club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] signed Baxter from Sunderland for a club record \u00a3100,000 fee, but his rapidly declining fitness and troubled personal life meant the move was unsuccessful. ''[[Nottingham Evening Post]]'' reporter Tony Pritchett described the signing of Baxter as \"probably the worst transfer in Forest's history\". After 49 appearances, he left Forest in May 1969 to return to Rangers.<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news|title=Baxter the shooting star Nottingham Forest chapter started the rapid decline of a glittering career|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12171071.Baxter_the_shooting_star_Nottingham_Forest_chapter_started_the_rapid_decline_of_a_glittering_career/|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=The Herald|date=21 April 2001|location=Glasgow}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Rangers===\nBaxter moved back to Rangers.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> His return to Rangers was brief, as he retired from football in 1970, aged only 31.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /> By the end of his career with Rangers he had made 254 appearances for the club, including victories that led to three Scottish League Championships, three Scottish Cups and four League Cups.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" />\n\n==International career==\nIn the 1960s Baxter gained 34 [[Cap (sport)|cap]]s as a member of strong [[Scotland national football team|Scottish teams]], which included [[Billy McNeill]], [[Pat Crerand]],<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> [[John White (footballer born 1937)|John White]], [[Dave Mackay]], [[Denis Law]]<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> and [[John Greig]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0,,5~1561270,00.html | accessdate=5 January 2009 | title=John Greig | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822193123/http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0%2C%2C5~1561270%2C00.html | archivedate=22 August 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his international appearances he scored three goals, and Scotland won 21, drew 3 and lost 10 of these matches.<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" /> He made his international debut in November 1960, when Scotland beat [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" /> In 1961 Scotland had lost 9\u20133 to [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], and April 1962 Baxter and Crerand played brilliantly, helping Scotland to gain some revenge with a 2\u20130 win.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=The Essential Shankly: Revealing the Kop Legend Who Launched a Thousand Quips |last=Keith |first=John |publisher=Robson |year=2001 |isbn=1-86105-465-3 |chapter=Funny Gags and Short Jabs |page=161 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=5ZdDpQI2W8EC&pg=PA161&dq=%22jim+baxter%22+%22world+cup%22#PPA161,M1 | accessdate=7 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to many commentators, his greatest performances were against England in 1963 and 1967.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"UEFABaxter\" /><ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> Baxter regarded his performance in 1963 as the better of the two.<ref>{{cite video |people=Jim Baxter |title=The Jim Baxter Story |medium=DVD |publisher=John Williams Productions - JW129 |date=2001}}</ref> In the 1963 game Scotland were reduced to 10 men when their [[left back]] [[Eric Caldow]]'s leg was broken in a tackle by [[Bobby Smith (footballer, born 1933)|Bobby Smith]] \u2013 [[Substitute (football)|substitution]]s were not allowed at that time.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> Baxter, supported by Mackay, White and Law,<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> led Scotland to a 2\u20131 win, scoring both of the goals, the first being Baxter's first-ever [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], for an English foul on [[Willie Henderson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Flower of Scotland stirs the passions |last=Shaw |first=Phil |date=14 October 1999 |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/flower-of-scotland-stirs-the-passions-742823.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |location=London}}</ref> [[Bobby Moore]] thought this was the best team Scotland ever fielded.<ref name=\"Powell2002\" />\n\nThe following year Scotland, again inspired by Baxter and Law, beat England 1\u20130, and only poor finishing prevented them from scoring a bigger win. In 1966, sixteen months after his leg had been broken, Baxter was not able to inspire his teammates, and Scotland lost 4\u20133 to England.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" />\n\nIn the 1967 [[British Home Championship]], Baxter produced a dominating but controversial performance for Scotland, tantalising England, who had won the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in 1966,<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> by playing \"[[keepie uppie]]\" (ball juggling) while waiting for teammates to get into good positions.<ref name=\"Holt1990SportAndBritish\">{{cite book |title=Sport and the British: A Modern History |last=Holt |first=Richard |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1990 |isbn=0-19-285229-9 |chapter=Englishness and Britishness |page=260 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=vtChCoG6veMC&pg=PA260&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP12,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> Some commentators accepted that humiliating the opposition was a valid objective, while others regarded it as childish and thought Scotland should have won a more convincing victory than the actual 3\u20132 scoreline.<ref name=\"SportAndNationalIdentity\">{{cite book |title=Sport and National Identity in the Post-war World |editor1=Smith, Adrian |editor2=Porter, Dilwyn |publisher=Routledge |year=2004 |isbn=0-415-28300-0 |chapter=Cry for Us, Argentina: Sport and national identity in late twentieth-century Scotland |first=Ronald |last=Kowalski |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yZfYh7n2qTMC&pg=PA74&dq=%22Sport+and+National+Identity+in+the+Post-war+World%22+jim+baxter |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Association Game: A History of British Football |last=Taylor |first=Matthew |publisher=Pearson Education |year=2008 |isbn=0-582-50596-8 |chapter=Glory and Decline, 1961-1985 |pages=296\u2013297 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J5oqBHq0XrEC&pg=PA296&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP8,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> Teammate Denis Law expressed opinions on both sides of this debate, saying that Baxter was \"the best player on the park\" and the main reason for the Scots' victory,<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\" /> but complaining that Baxter's lack of urgency had prevented Scotland from thoroughly avenging the 9\u20133 defeat in April 1961.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\">{{cite news |title=Jim Baxter |date=16 April 2001 |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Dalyell |first=Tam |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/jim-baxter-7784802.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"SportAndNationalIdentity\" /> [[Alex Ferguson]] said Baxter's performance \"could have been set to music\".<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> In this game Baxter also conspired with [[Billy Bremner]] against [[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]], sending Bremner a \"50-50\" pass, which allowed Bremner to \"hit Ball like a train\" when Ball contested possession.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> As Scotland were the first team to beat England after the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], the [[Tartan Army]] proclaimed themselves \"[[Unofficial Football World Championships|unofficial world champions]]\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/jun/08/theknowledge.sport |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Zimbabwe: Kings of the world |last1=Dart |first1=James |last2=Ahmed |first2=Zohaib |date=8 June 2005 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1963, which may have been Baxter's best year overall, he played for the \"[[World XI|Rest of the world]]\" in [[1963 England v Rest of the World football match|a match against England]] to celebrate the [[centenary]] of [[The Football Association]].<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> He came on to the field in the second half, and his performance won the admiration of [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]].<ref name=\"IndependentSelfconfidentMaster\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/baxter-a-selfconfident-master-of-sublime-skills-681499.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Baxter a self-confident master of sublime skills |first=Ken |last=Jones |date=16 April 2001 |work=[[The Independent]] |location=London}}</ref> However England won the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/Archive/matchstats.html?m=373 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20071029051823/http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/Archive/matchstats.html?m=373 |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 October 2007 |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=England v Rest of World, 23 October 1963}}</ref>\n\nScotland did not qualify for the final stage of the [[FIFA World Cup]] during Baxter's playing career. Scottish public opinion at the time blamed lack of commitment by the \"Anglos\", Scottish-born players who spent little or none of their playing careers in Scotland.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Association Game: A History of British Football |last=Taylor |first=Matthew |publisher=Pearson Education |year=2008 |isbn=0-582-50596-8 |chapter=Glory and Decline, 1961-1985 |page=100 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J5oqBHq0XrEC&pg=PA296&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP8,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> However at the time beating England was more important to the Scots.<ref name=\"Powell2002\">{{cite book |title=Bobby Moore: The Life and Times of a Sporting Hero |last=Powell |first=Jeff |publisher=Robson Books Ltd |edition=2 |year=2002 |isbn=1-86105-511-0 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Cw3BkpXDOWQC&pg=PA121&dq=%22scotland%22+%22world+cup%22#PPA121,M1 |accessdate=7 January 2009 |chapter=Bloody Foreigners |pages=121=122 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Power, Corruption and Pies: Volume 2 |publisher=WSC Books Limited |year=2006 |isbn=0-9540134-8-4 |chapter=Working from Home |last=Gall |first=Ken |pages=154\u2013155 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HuTdMMRxFucC&pg=PA155&dq=%22jim+baxter%22+%22world+cup%22#PPA155,M1 | accessdate=7 January 2009}}</ref> In 1960\u201361, when Baxter played in all the qualifying matches for the [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962 World Cup]], they finished first equal in their qualifying group but lost the play-off against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]],<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\">{{cite web | url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/jamescurranbaxter.html | accessdate=7 January 2009 | title=Jim Baxter - Scotland Football Record from 09 Nov 1960 to 22 Nov 1967 |publisher=London Hearts Supporters Club}}</ref> who were runners-up to Brazil in the Final.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=21/index.html |accessdate=7 January 2009 | title=1962 FIFA World Cup Chile | publisher=[[FIFA]] }}</ref> Four years later Baxter played in only two of the qualifying games, (however one of these games was against Italy where he made John Greig's winning goal after starting the move by taking the ball from Scotland's keeper)<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" /> before breaking his leg in a club game in Vienna.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> Scotland finished second in their qualifying group, behind [[Italian national football team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1966/wc66qualification.html | accessdate=7 January 2009 | title=World Cup 1966: The Qualification Rounds }}</ref> In 1968\u201369 he was not selected to play in any of the qualifiers for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]].<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" />\n\n==Personal life and retirement==\nAfter moving to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], Baxter became a notorious womaniser. In his words, \"One day, I was a [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] player who couldnae pull the birds at the [[Cowdenbeath]] Palais. The next day I was in [[Glasgow]] and the girls were throwing themselves at me. It was certainly a change and I wasn't letting it go by.\" However, in 1965 he married Jean Ferguson, a hairdresser, and the couple brought up two sons Alan and Steven. His marriage to Jean broke down in 1981 and the two divorced. Jean married golfer William McCondichie three years later.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> In 1983 Baxter formed a relationship with Norma Morton, and the couple remained together until his death in 2001.<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph2001TrueBraveheart\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/leagues/scottishpremier/3003687/Last-lament-for-true-braveheart.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Last lament for true braveheart |last=Cramb |first=Auslan |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=20 April 2001}}</ref>\n\nBaxter was free of the [[Sectarianism in Glasgow|sectarianism]] that marked the rivalry between [[Glasgow]]'s two leading teams. His close friends included the Celtic players [[Billy McNeill]], [[Pat Crerand]] and [[Mike Jackson (footballer)|Mike Jackson]], in defiance of the unwritten rule that rivals did not associate.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/scotland/article2652410.ece |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Firm pals who broke the Glasgow mould |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |last=Baillie |first=Rodger |location=London |date=14 October 2007}}</ref>\n\nLike some other British football stars of the late 20th century, Baxter drank to excess,<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /><ref name=\"MudSweatBeers\">{{cite book |title=Mud, Sweat and Beers: A Cultural History of Sport and Alcohol |last1=Collins |first1=Tony |last2=Vamplew |first2=Wray |publisher=Berg Publishers |year=2002 |isbn=1-85973-558-4 |chapter=A Little of What Does You Good? |page=[https://archive.org/details/mudsweatbeerscul0000coll/page/104 104] |url=https://archive.org/details/mudsweatbeerscul0000coll |url-access=registration |quote=jim baxter football rangers. |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> and at one point was said to be consuming three bottles of [[Bacardi]] a day.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> Scotland teammate [[Dave Mackay (footballer born 1934)|Dave Mackay]] unsuccessfully advised him to train harder and live more sensibly.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> Baxter often got falling-down drunk the night before a match, but this did not seem to hamper his play, and team managers took little notice of his drinking.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /> After retiring from football Baxter became a [[pub]] licensee, an unsuitable career for a problem drinker.<ref name=\"MudSweatBeers\" /> At the age of 55 he needed two [[liver]] [[organ transplant|transplants]] in four days,<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"MudSweatBeers\" /> and promised to quit drinking.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" />\n\nHis other lifelong addiction was gambling, at which he lost \u00a3500,000 by his own estimate and \u00a3250,000 by third-party estimates.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/apr/16/guardianobituaries.football |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Jim Baxter |last=Glenn |first=Patrick |date=16 April 2001 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> Later in his life, when asked if earning the huge incomes of footballers in later decades would have made a difference, he replied, \"Aye, I would have gambled \u00a350,000 a week on the horses instead of \u00a3100.\" <ref name=\"BBCStatue\" />\n\nIn February 2001, Baxter was diagnosed as suffering from [[cancer]] of the [[pancreas]], and he died at his home on Glasgow's [[Glasgow#South Side|South Side]] on 14 April 2001, with his partner Norma and his sons Alan and Steven at his bedside.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> His funeral was held in [[Glasgow Cathedral]], where a reading was given by [[Gordon Brown]], a long-time fan of [[Raith Rovers F.C.]], where Baxter began his career.<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph2001TrueBraveheart\" />\n\n==Style of play==\nBaxter is generally regarded as one of Scotland's greatest ever players.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /> He was noted for accurate passes, for sending opponents the wrong way with a swivel of his hips, and for inspiring teammates with his confident approach.<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph2001TrueBraveheart\" /> He attracted attention by his stylish play, controlling the game with \"unhurried artistry\". He refused to conform with the \"efficient\" style that dominated British football or the energetic, physical style that was typical of Rangers at the time.<ref name=\"Holt1990SportAndBritish\" /> Indeed, although Rangers insisted that players tuck their shirts completely into their shorts, Baxter always let part of his dangle over his left hip.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0,,5~1561270,00.html | accessdate=15 April 2009 | title=Jim Baxter | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822193123/http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0%2C%2C5~1561270%2C00.html | archivedate=22 August 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He described his approach to playing football as \"treating the ball like a woman. Give it a cuddle, caress it a wee bit, take your time, and you'll get the required response\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Football Talk: The Language & Folklore of the World's Greatest Game |last=Seddon |first=Peter |publisher=Robson |year=2004 |isbn=1-86105-683-4 |chapter=Nothing but a Bag of Wind? |page=49 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7N3iYWotTPYC&pg=PA49&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP7,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nBaxter played most of his best football in his early twenties, before the leg fracture against [[Rapid Vienna]] in December 1964 and the start of his heavy drinking that made his nickname \"Slim Jim\" less appropriate.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = http://sport.scotsman.com/top-stories/Flawed-legend--and-greater.2251226.jp |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Flawed legend - and greater for it |last=Pattullo |first=Alan |work=[[The Scotsman]] }}</ref>\nHe was also noted as a joker on the pitch.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> After the [[replay (sports)|replay]] of the [[Scottish Cup]] Final against Celtic in 1963 he stuffed the match ball up his shirt and later gave it to a new member of the team. The [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] insisted that the ball should be returned, and Rangers sent them a ball, but possibly not the match ball.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/2008/12/22/night-slim-jim-had-a-ball-86908-20989029/ |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Night Slim Jim Had A Ball |date=22 December 2008 |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]}}</ref> Most famously, during Scotland's 3\u20132 win over England in 1967, he taunted his opponents by playing \"[[keepie uppie]]\" during the game.<ref name=\"Holt1990SportAndBritish\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Jim Baxter statue Hill Of Beath.jpg|thumb|Statue in Baxter's honour in his home town, [[Hill of Beath]] in [[Fife]] \u2013 with the ball on his famous left foot]]\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] manager [[Alex Ferguson]] described Baxter as \"arguably the best player to play in Scottish football\"<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3003288/Baxter-best-to-play-in-Scottish-football.html | accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Baxter 'best to play in Scottish football' |last=Gray |first=William |date=15 April 2001 |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |location=London}}</ref> and \"the greatest player I ever played with&nbsp;... He had touch, balance, vision and just this wonderful aura&nbsp;...\" Rangers manager [[Willie Waddell]] said, \"Jim was the finest [[left half]] ever produced by Rangers.\" [[Jimmy Johnstone]], who played for Rangers' great rivals Celtic, said shortly after Baxter's death, \"He was a great man and a genius on the ball.\"<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\">{{cite news |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |date=15 April 2001 |last=McGill |first=Craig |title=Slim Jim Baxter 1939 - 2001: Death of a Legend |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/SLIM+JIM+BAXTER+1939+-+2001%3A+DEATH+OF+A+LEGEND%3B+He+was+one+of+the...-a073218048 |accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref> Allegedly [[Pel\u00e9]] once said that Baxter should have been a [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian]].<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /> After Baxter's performance in the 1963 \"rest of the world\" vs England match, [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]] asked, \"Where has this fellow been hiding?\"<ref name=\"IndependentSelfconfidentMaster\" /> Shortly before his own death, [[George Best]] named Baxter as one of the best eleven players he had played with or against in an interview with [[FourFourTwo]] magazine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/george-best-perfect-xi |title=George Best: Perfect XI |last=Massarella |first=Louis |date=December 2005 |website=Four Four Two |accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nBaxter is a member of the Rangers supporters' Hall of Fame,<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /> and one of the first 50 added to the Scottish Sporting Hall of Fame when it was created in 2002.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/2530435.stm |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Scotland honours sporting legends |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=30 November 2002}}</ref><ref name=SSHOF>{{cite web|url=http://www.sshf.co.uk/inductees/a-f/jim-baxter/|title=Scottish Sports Hall of Fame: Jim Baxter|publisher=[[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame]]|date=|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> In 2004, he was also inducted into the [[Scottish Football Hall of Fame]].<ref name=SHOF>{{cite web |url=http://scottishfootballhalloffame.co.uk/jim-baxter/ |title=Scottish Football Hall of Fame - Jim Baxter|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> In the December 1999 issue of [[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer magazine]] he was voted by a readers' poll into a list of the [[World Soccer (magazine)#The Greatest Players of the 20th century|100 greatest players of the 20th century]].<ref>{{cite web|title=World Soccer Players of the Century (2001)|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamHons/HonsWldSocPlyrsCent.html|website=England Football Online|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tartan Army]] unsuccessfully attempted to get the new [[Wembley Stadium]] footbridge named after him,<ref>{{cite book \n| title=The Unofficial Football World Championships: An Alternative Soccer History |last=Brown |first=Paul |publisher=Tonto Books |year=2006|isbn=0-9552183-1-4 |chapter=Classic Matches |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XktTup3O-fQC&pg=PA74&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPA5,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lda.gov.uk/server/show/ConWebDoc.1071 |accessdate=6 January 2008 |title=Battle of the bridge commences |publisher=London Development Agency |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050518091028/http://www.lda.gov.uk/server/show/ConWebDoc.1071 |archivedate=18 May 2005}}</ref> and on 24 February 2005 [[Scottish National Party]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] [[Pete Wishart]] presented an [[Early Day Motion]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] supporting this campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.currybet.net/cbet_blog/2005/03/baxter_vs_moore.php |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Baxter vs Moore - Costing you money in Parliament }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westminster.snp.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1378&Itemid=40 |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=SNP MP's motion backs Jim Baxter bridge at Wembley |publisher=[[Scottish National Party]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070620025818/http://www.westminster.snp.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1378&Itemid=40 |archivedate=20 June 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, a statue of Baxter was erected in his birthplace, [[Hill of Beath]] in [[Fife]], after a campaign that raised \u00a380,000.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /><ref name=\"BBCStatue\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2962041.stm |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Statue to football legend unveiled |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=20 April 2003 }}</ref> Fellow footballer and midfielder [[Scott Brown (footballer, born June 1985)|Scott Brown]], who would become Scotland captain in the 2010s, was also raised in the village and attended the same school, with the Baxter statue across the street from his childhood home,<ref name=Brown>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/top-football-stories/slim-jim-watching-over-hibs-kid-scott-1-878028|title=Slim Jim watching over Hibs kid Scott|work=The Scotsman|first=David|last=Hardie|date=6 May 2003|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> although Brown chose to sign for Celtic rather than Rangers.<ref name=\"Guardian 16May2007\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/16/newsstory.sport6|title=Celtic bag Brown from under Rangers' nose|work=The Guardian |first=Mark |last=Atkinson |date=16 May 2007|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International appearances===\n:Sources:<ref name=NFT/><ref name=fsscot/><ref name=SFA/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1960||1||0\n|-\n|1961||7||0\n|-\n|1962||4||1\n|-\n|1963||7||2\n|-\n|1964||5||0\n|-\n|1965||3||0\n|-\n|1966||4||0\n|-\n|1967||3||0\n|-\n!Total||34||3\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Scotland's goal tally first.''<ref name=NFT>{{NFT|18038|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=fsscot>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotland/player.php?playerid=739|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Scotland|work=Fitbastats|date=|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=SFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=2492&playerid=112900|title=Jim Baxter profile|publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]] |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 2 May 1962 || [[Hampden Park]], [[Glasgow]] || {{fb|URU}} || 1\u20133 || 2\u20133 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 2.\n| rowspan=2 | 6 April 1963 || rowspan=2 | [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], [[London]] || rowspan=2 | {{fb|ENG}} || 1\u20130 || rowspan=2 | 2\u20131 || rowspan=2 | [[1963 British Home Championship]]\n|-\n| 3.\n| 2\u20130\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Rangers'''\n*[[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] Runner-up: [[1960\u201361 European Cup Winners' Cup|1960\u201361]]<ref name=fs60161>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=6|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1960\u201361|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[List of Scottish football champions#Scottish League First Division (1893\u20131975)|Scottish League First Division]]: [[1960\u201361 Scottish First Division|1960\u201361]],<ref name=fs60161/> [[1962\u201363 Scottish First Division|1962\u201363]],<ref name=fs6263>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=4|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1962\u201363|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> [[1963\u201364 Scottish First Division|1963\u201364]]<ref name=fs6364>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=3|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1963\u201364|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> \n*[[Scottish Cup]]: [[1961\u201362 Scottish Cup|1961\u201362]],<ref name=fs6162>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=5|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1961\u201362|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> [[1962\u201363 Scottish Cup|1962\u201363]],<ref name=fs6263/> [[1963\u201364 Scottish Cup|1963\u201364]]<ref name=fs6364/>\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[1960\u201361 Scottish League Cup|1960\u201361]],<ref name=fs60161/> [[1961\u201362 Scottish League Cup|1961\u201362]],<ref name=fs6162/> [[1963\u201364 Scottish League Cup|1963\u201364]],<ref name=fs6364/> [[1964\u201365 Scottish League Cup|1964\u201365]]<ref name=fs6465>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=2|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1964\u201365|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Scottish Football Hall of Fame]] (inaugural inductee)<ref name=SHOF/>\n*[[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame#Football|Scottish Sports Hall of Fame]] (inaugural inductee)<ref name=SSHOF/>\n*[[Ballon d'Or]]: [[1965 Ballon d'Or|1965]] (13th place)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy65.html |title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1965 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=22 June 2005 |accessdate=24 October 2016 |first=Pierrend |last=Jos\u00e9 Luis}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{SFA profile}}\n* [http://www.glasgowguide.co.uk/images_jbf1.html Jim Baxter's Funeral Images @ Glasgow Guide]\n* {{NeilBrownPlayers|player/jimbaxter}}\n\n{{Rangers F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{Scottish Football Hall of Fame}}\n{{Raith Rovers F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baxter, Jim}}\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:People from Hill of Beath]]\n[[Category:People educated at Beath High School]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:Raith Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Black Watch soldiers]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fife]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Crossgates Primrose F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Royals players]]\n[[Category:United Soccer Association players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Australian rules footballer|Jim Baxter (Australian footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| image          = Jim Baxter in Scotland shirt.png\n| caption        = Baxter during his time at [[Nottingham Forest]]\n| fullname       = James Curran Baxter<ref>{{Hugman|1167|accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1939|9|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Hill of Beath]], [[Fife]], Scotland\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|2001|4|14|1939|9|29|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Glasgow]], Scotland<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/1179640.stm |title=Rangers legend Baxter dies |work=BBC Sport |date=14 April 2001 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> \n| position       = [[Wing half|Left-half]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = Halbeath Juveniles\n| youthyears2 = \n| youthclubs2 = [[Crossgates Primrose J.F.C.|Crossgates Primrose]]\n| years1         = 1957\u20131960\n| years2         = 1960\u20131965\n| years3         = 1965\u20131967\n| years4         = 1967\n| years5         = 1967\u20131969\n| years6         = 1969\u20131970\n| clubs1         = [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]\n| clubs2         = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| clubs3         = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| clubs4         = \u2192 [[Vancouver Royals|Vancouver Royal Canadians]] (loan)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasljerseys.com/Players/B/Baxter.Jim.htm |work=North American Soccer League Players |title=NASL profile - Jim Baxter |accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n| clubs5         = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| clubs6         = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps1          = 62\n| goals1         = 3\n| caps2          = 136\n| goals2         = 18\n| caps3          = 87\n| goals3         = 10\n| caps4          = 12\n| goals4         = 2\n| caps5          = 48\n| goals5         = 3\n| caps6          = 14\n| goals6         = 1\n| totalcaps      = 359\n| totalgoals     = 37\n| nationalyears1 = 1958<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu23/player.php?playerid=52|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Scotland Under-23|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n| nationalteam1  = [[Scotland national under-23 football team|Scotland Under-23]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1960<ref name=scot60s>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lITgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT215&lpg=PT215&dq=1964+%22scotland+XI%22+v+%22scottish+league%22&source=bl&ots=DjEqsyzxpo&sig=ACfU3U1by2fCMyV966wejpqXzOUTR3RFdw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjU-d_FrZ_jAhVmRRUIHVsBCm4Q6AEwCXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22scotland%20XI%22%20v%20%22scottish%20league%22&f=false|title=Scotland in the 60s: The Definitive Account of the Scottish National Football Side During the 1960s|author=Ronnie McDevitt|year=2016|publisher=Pitch Publishing|isbn=9781785312458}}</ref>\n| nationalteam2 = [[List of Scottish Football League representative players#Scotland trial matches / SFL Centenary players|SFL trial v SFA]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 1\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1960\u20131967\n| nationalteam3  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 34\n| nationalgoals3 = 3\n| nationalyears4 = 1961\u20131964<ref name=scot60s/>\n| nationalteam4 = [[List of Scottish Football League representative players#Scotland trial matches / SFL Centenary players|SFA trial v SFL]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 2\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 1961\u20131964<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/jamescurranbaxter.html|title=Matches played by James Curran Baxter for Scottish Football League XI|publisher=London Hearts Supporters Club |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n| nationalteam5  = [[Scottish Football League XI|Scottish League XI]]\n| nationalcaps5  = 5\n| nationalgoals5 = 0\n}}\n\n'''James Curran Baxter''' (29 September 1939 \u2013 14 April 2001) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[wing half|left half]]. He is generally regarded as one of the country's greatest ever players. He was born, educated and started his career in [[Fife]], but his peak playing years were in the early 1960s with the [[Glasgow]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], whom he helped to win ten trophies between 1960 and 1965, and where he became known as \"Slim Jim\". However, he started drinking heavily during a four-month layoff caused by a leg fracture in December 1964, his fitness suffered, and he was [[Transfer (football)|transferred]] to [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in summer 1965. In two and a half years at Sunderland he played 98 games and scored 12 goals, becoming known for drinking himself unconscious the night before a match and playing well the next day. At the end of 1967 Sunderland transferred him to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], who gave him a [[Free transfer (football)|free transfer]] back to Rangers in 1969 after 50 games. After a further year with Rangers Baxter retired from football in 1970, at the age of 31.\n\nFrom 1960 to 1967, he was a leading member of a strong Scottish international team that lost only once to [[England national football team|England]], in 1965, shortly after he recovered from the leg fracture. He thought his best international performance was a 2\u20131 win against England in 1963, when he scored both goals after Scotland were reduced to 10 players. In the 1967 match against England, who had won the [[1966 FIFA World Cup|1966 World Cup]], he taunted the opposition by ball juggling while waiting for his teammates to find good positions. Although he was given most of the credit for the 3\u20132 win, some commentators wished he had made an effort to run up a bigger score.\n\nIn his prime, Baxter was known for his ability to raise a team's morale, his good tactical vision, precise passing and ability to send opponents the wrong way \u2013 and for being a joker on the pitch. He also broke with Glasgow tradition by becoming friendly with several members of their major [[Old Firm|Glasgow rivals]], [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].\n\nAlthough he gained a reputation as a womaniser when he moved to Glasgow, he married in 1965 and had two sons. The marriage broke up in 1981, and in 1983 he formed another relationship that lasted the rest of his life. After retiring from football he became manager of a [[Public house|pub]], and his continued heavy drinking damaged his liver so badly that he needed two [[Organ transplant|transplant]]s at the age of 55, after which he swore off [[Alcoholic beverage|alcohol]]. Baxter was also addicted to gambling, and is estimated to have lost between \u00a3250,000 and \u00a3500,000. After he died of [[pancreatic cancer]] in 2001, his funeral was held in [[Glasgow Cathedral]] and his ashes were buried at Rangers' [[Ibrox Stadium]]. In 2003, a statue was erected in his honour at his hometown, [[Hill of Beath]].\n\n==Early life==\nBaxter was born in [[Hill of Beath]], [[Fife]], on 29 September 1939 and was educated and started his career there. After leaving school he spent eight months as an apprentice [[Cabinet making|cabinet maker]], and then worked as a coal miner.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" />\n\nHis former headmaster James Carmichael took an interest in ex-pupils and encouraged Baxter to join local football team Halbeath Juveniles instead of one of the glamour clubs.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> Baxter went on to play for the Fife junior team, [[Crossgates Primrose J.F.C.|Crossgates Primrose]].<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" />\n\n==Club career==\n===Raith Rovers===\nBaxter joined [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] as a part-timer in 1957.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> In his time at Raith he orchestrated a 3-2 win over Rangers at Ibrox. [[Scot Symon]] decided he wanted to sign him for Rangers from that performance.\n\nIn an interview on his career, Baxter was asked if joining the senior ranks was the beginning of his football education. He said he found the idea of being given any sort of football education laughable,  before then commenting on [[Willie McNaught]]. Describing McNaught as, 'a smashing guy', Baxter explained how instead of thoughtlessly charging forward with the ball, McNaught suggested more considered football \u2013 change from running 30 yards to produce a five-yard pass to running five yards and producing a 30-yard pass. This, Baxter then stated, was his football education with Willie McNaught the provider.<ref name = \"qoswillie\">{{cite web |url=http://www.qosfc.com/new_newsview.aspx?newsid=1215 |title=Willie McNaught (and Ken) |work=Queen of the South official website |date=26 April 2012 |accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref> He later said of his time with the two Fife clubs, \"I would never have made it in today's circumstances. I needed bastards like Carmichael, Buckard, Ferrier, [[Bert Herdman|Herdman]] and McNaught. Young players like I was would simply tell them to get stuffed and take their talent elsewhere. I owe them.\"<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" />\n\n===Rangers===\nIn June 1960,<ref name=\"UEFABaxter\">{{cite web|title=On This Day: 29 September |publisher=[[UEFA]] |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/history/OnThisDay/index,newsid=216506.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209071201/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/history/onthisday/index%2Cnewsid%3D216506.html |archivedate= 9 December 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> he joined the [[Glasgow]] team [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] for a [[transfer fee]] of \u00a317,500, a Scottish record at the time.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\"/><!--\nhttp://www.uefa.com/uefa/history/OnThisDay/index,newsid=216506.html not on Internet Archive on 24 September 2010, try again in Mar 2011\n-->\n\nBaxter played for Rangers from 1960 to 1965, mainly as an attacking [[left half]]. During this period the team won the [[Scottish Football League Premier Division|Scottish League]] Championship in 1961, 1963 and 1964,<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> and were winners of three [[Scottish Cup]]s and four [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]s from as many finals, Baxter playing in all seven ties.<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\" /> Rangers fans remember him as \"Slim Jim\", and in 18 \"[[Old Firm]]\" games against local rivals [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] \u2013 ten Scottish League, five League Cup and three Scottish Cup matches \u2013 he was only twice on the losing side.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /> His first Rangers game  was in August 1960 at [[inside left]] against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in the Scottish League Cup. He scored his first goal for the club in November 1960, against [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]],<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> and in the same month scored an early goal in Rangers' 8\u20130 win over the German team [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]].<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> In [[1961 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1961]] Baxter played in the Rangers team that contested the first ever [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] Final, a [[two-legged tie]] that they lost 4\u20131 on aggregate to [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref name=\"RSSSF ECWC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec196061.html#cwc |title=Cup Winners' Cup 1960-61 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |accessdate=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n \nIn December 1964, Baxter played brilliantly to set up a 2\u20130 win for Rangers in an away game against [[SK Rapid Wien|Rapid Vienna]] in the [[1964\u201365 European Cup|European Cup]]. With the game won, rather than play out time Baxter's confidence over-extended into arrogance to make fun of his opponents with the ball. In the last minute he went to 'nutmeg' an opponent, who was having none of it and broke Baxter's leg with his challenge.<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\" /> This was to be a watershed for Baxter. During the four months in which he was unable to play he began drinking to his detriment; this ultimately was to curtail his playing career and his life.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" />\n\n===Sunderland===\nBaxter joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] for a [[transfer fee]] of \u00a372,500, the highest ever paid to a Scottish club at the time.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /><ref name=\"IndependentSelfconfidentMaster\" /> Baxter played 98 games for Sunderland in England's First Division (then the top tier), scoring 12 goals.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\">{{cite book |title=Black Catalogue: We are Sunderland |editor=Ken Gambles |publisher=PDG Books Ltd |year=2005 |isbn=1-905519-02-8 |last=Robson |first=Barry |chapter=The One and Only, Slim Jim |pages=1\u20134 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7t2rTXPLs-oC&pg=PA3&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPA1,M1 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianObit\" />\n\n===Nottingham Forest===\nIn December 1967, English First Division club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] signed Baxter from Sunderland for a club record \u00a3100,000 fee, but his rapidly declining fitness and troubled personal life meant the move was unsuccessful. ''[[Nottingham Evening Post]]'' reporter Tony Pritchett described the signing of Baxter as \"probably the worst transfer in Forest's history\". After 49 appearances, he left Forest in May 1969 to return to Rangers.<ref name=\"Herald\">{{cite news|title=Baxter the shooting star Nottingham Forest chapter started the rapid decline of a glittering career|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12171071.Baxter_the_shooting_star_Nottingham_Forest_chapter_started_the_rapid_decline_of_a_glittering_career/|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=The Herald|date=21 April 2001|location=Glasgow}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Rangers===\nBaxter moved back to Rangers.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> His return to Rangers was brief, as he retired from football in 1970, aged only 31.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /> By the end of his career with Rangers he had made 254 appearances for the club, including victories that led to three Scottish League Championships, three Scottish Cups and four League Cups.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" />\n\n==International career==\nIn the 1960s Baxter gained 34 [[Cap (sport)|cap]]s as a member of strong [[Scotland national football team|Scottish teams]], which included [[Billy McNeill]], [[Pat Crerand]],<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> [[John White (footballer born 1937)|John White]], [[Dave Mackay]], [[Denis Law]]<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> and [[John Greig]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0,,5~1561270,00.html | accessdate=5 January 2009 | title=John Greig | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822193123/http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0%2C%2C5~1561270%2C00.html | archivedate=22 August 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In his international appearances he scored three goals, and Scotland won 21, drew 3 and lost 10 of these matches.<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" /> He made his international debut in November 1960, when Scotland beat [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]].<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" /> In 1961 Scotland had lost 9\u20133 to [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley]], and April 1962 Baxter and Crerand played brilliantly, helping Scotland to gain some revenge with a 2\u20130 win.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /><ref>{{cite book |title=The Essential Shankly: Revealing the Kop Legend Who Launched a Thousand Quips |last=Keith |first=John |publisher=Robson |year=2001 |isbn=1-86105-465-3 |chapter=Funny Gags and Short Jabs |page=161 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=5ZdDpQI2W8EC&pg=PA161&dq=%22jim+baxter%22+%22world+cup%22#PPA161,M1 | accessdate=7 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to many commentators, his greatest performances were against England in 1963 and 1967.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"UEFABaxter\" /><ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> Baxter regarded his performance in 1963 as the better of the two.<ref>{{cite video |people=Jim Baxter |title=The Jim Baxter Story |medium=DVD |publisher=John Williams Productions - JW129 |date=2001}}</ref> In the 1963 game Scotland were reduced to 10 men when their [[left back]] [[Eric Caldow]]'s leg was broken in a tackle by [[Bobby Smith (footballer, born 1933)|Bobby Smith]] \u2013 [[Substitute (football)|substitution]]s were not allowed at that time.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" />  Baxter, supported by Mackay, White and Law,<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> led Scotland to a 2\u20131 win, scoring both of the goals,  the first being Baxter's first-ever [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], for an English foul on [[Willie Henderson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Flower of Scotland stirs the passions |last=Shaw |first=Phil |date=14 October 1999 |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/flower-of-scotland-stirs-the-passions-742823.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |location=London}}</ref> [[Bobby Moore]] thought this was the best team Scotland ever fielded.<ref name=\"Powell2002\" />\n\nThe following year Scotland, again inspired by Baxter and Law, beat England 1\u20130, and only poor finishing prevented them from scoring a bigger win. In 1966, sixteen months after his leg had been broken, Baxter was not able to inspire his teammates, and Scotland lost 4\u20133 to England.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" />\n\nIn the 1967 [[British Home Championship]], Baxter produced a dominating but controversial performance for Scotland, tantalising England, who had won the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in 1966,<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> by playing \"[[keepie uppie]]\" (ball juggling) while waiting for teammates to get into good positions.<ref name=\"Holt1990SportAndBritish\">{{cite book |title=Sport and the British: A Modern History |last=Holt |first=Richard |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1990 |isbn=0-19-285229-9 |chapter=Englishness and Britishness |page=260 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=vtChCoG6veMC&pg=PA260&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP12,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> Some commentators accepted that humiliating the opposition was a valid objective, while others regarded it as childish and thought Scotland should have won a more convincing victory than the actual 3\u20132 scoreline.<ref name=\"SportAndNationalIdentity\">{{cite book |title=Sport and National Identity in the Post-war World |editor1=Smith, Adrian |editor2=Porter, Dilwyn |publisher=Routledge |year=2004 |isbn=0-415-28300-0 |chapter=Cry for Us, Argentina: Sport and national identity in late twentieth-century Scotland |first=Ronald |last=Kowalski |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yZfYh7n2qTMC&pg=PA74&dq=%22Sport+and+National+Identity+in+the+Post-war+World%22+jim+baxter |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Association Game: A History of British Football |last=Taylor |first=Matthew |publisher=Pearson Education |year=2008 |isbn=0-582-50596-8 |chapter=Glory and Decline, 1961-1985 |pages=296\u2013297 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J5oqBHq0XrEC&pg=PA296&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP8,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> Teammate Denis Law expressed opinions on both sides of this debate, saying that Baxter was \"the best player on the park\" and the main reason for the Scots' victory,<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\" /> but complaining that Baxter's lack of urgency had prevented Scotland from thoroughly avenging the 9\u20133 defeat in April 1961.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\">{{cite news |title=Jim Baxter |date=16 April 2001 |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Dalyell |first=Tam |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/jim-baxter-7784802.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"SportAndNationalIdentity\" /> [[Alex Ferguson]] said Baxter's performance \"could have been set to music\".<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> In this game Baxter also conspired with [[Billy Bremner]] against [[Alan Ball, Jr.|Alan Ball]], sending Bremner a \"50-50\" pass, which allowed Bremner to \"hit Ball like a train\" when Ball contested possession.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> As Scotland were the first team to beat England after the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]], the [[Tartan Army]] proclaimed themselves \"[[Unofficial Football World Championships|unofficial world champions]]\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/jun/08/theknowledge.sport |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Zimbabwe: Kings of the world |last1=Dart |first1=James |last2=Ahmed |first2=Zohaib |date=8 June 2005 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1963, which may have been Baxter's best year overall, he played for the \"[[World XI|Rest of the world]]\" in [[1963 England v Rest of the World football match|a match against England]] to celebrate the [[centenary]] of [[The Football Association]].<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> He came on to the field in the second half, and his performance won the admiration of [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]].<ref name=\"IndependentSelfconfidentMaster\">{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/scottish/baxter-a-selfconfident-master-of-sublime-skills-681499.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Baxter a self-confident master of sublime skills |first=Ken |last=Jones |date=16 April 2001 |work=[[The Independent]] |location=London}}</ref> However England won the match 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/Archive/matchstats.html?m=373 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20071029051823/http://www.thefa.com/England/SeniorTeam/Archive/matchstats.html?m=373 |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 October 2007 |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=England v Rest of World, 23 October 1963}}</ref>\n\nScotland did not qualify for the final stage of the [[FIFA World Cup]] during Baxter's playing career. Scottish public opinion at the time blamed lack of commitment by the \"Anglos\", Scottish-born players who spent little or none of their playing careers in Scotland.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Association Game: A History of British Football |last=Taylor |first=Matthew |publisher=Pearson Education |year=2008 |isbn=0-582-50596-8 |chapter=Glory and Decline, 1961-1985 |page=100 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J5oqBHq0XrEC&pg=PA296&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP8,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> However at the time beating England was more important to the Scots.<ref name=\"Powell2002\">{{cite book |title=Bobby Moore: The Life and Times of a Sporting Hero |last=Powell |first=Jeff |publisher=Robson Books Ltd |edition=2 |year=2002 |isbn=1-86105-511-0 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Cw3BkpXDOWQC&pg=PA121&dq=%22scotland%22+%22world+cup%22#PPA121,M1 |accessdate=7 January 2009 |chapter=Bloody Foreigners |pages=121=122 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Power, Corruption and Pies: Volume 2 |publisher=WSC Books Limited |year=2006 |isbn=0-9540134-8-4 |chapter=Working from Home |last=Gall |first=Ken |pages=154\u2013155 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HuTdMMRxFucC&pg=PA155&dq=%22jim+baxter%22+%22world+cup%22#PPA155,M1 | accessdate=7 January 2009}}</ref> In 1960\u201361, when Baxter played in all the qualifying matches for the [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962 World Cup]], they finished first equal in their qualifying group but lost the play-off against [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]],<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\">{{cite web | url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/jamescurranbaxter.html | accessdate=7 January 2009 | title=Jim Baxter - Scotland Football Record from 09 Nov 1960  to  22 Nov 1967  |publisher=London Hearts Supporters Club}}</ref> who were runners-up to Brazil in the Final.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=21/index.html |accessdate=7 January 2009 | title=1962 FIFA World Cup Chile | publisher=[[FIFA]] }}</ref> Four years later Baxter played in only two of the qualifying games, (however one of these games was against Italy where he made John Greig's winning goal after starting the move by taking the ball from Scotland's keeper)<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" /> before breaking his leg in a club game in Vienna.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> Scotland finished second in their qualifying group, behind [[Italian national football team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.planetworldcup.com/CUPS/1966/wc66qualification.html | accessdate=7 January 2009 | title=World Cup 1966: The Qualification Rounds }}</ref> In 1968\u201369 he was not selected to play in any of the qualifiers for the [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970 World Cup]].<ref name=\"LondonHeartsBaxter\" />\n\n==Personal life and retirement==\nAfter moving to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], Baxter became a notorious womaniser. In his words, \"One day, I was a [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] player who couldnae pull the birds at the [[Cowdenbeath]] Palais. The next day I was in [[Glasgow]] and the girls were throwing themselves at me. It was certainly a change and I wasn't letting it go by.\" However, in 1965 he married Jean Ferguson, a hairdresser, and the couple brought up two sons Alan and Steven. His marriage to Jean broke down in 1981 and the two divorced. Jean married golfer William McCondichie three years later.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> In 1983 Baxter formed a relationship with Norma Morton, and the couple remained together until his death in 2001.<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph2001TrueBraveheart\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/leagues/scottishpremier/3003687/Last-lament-for-true-braveheart.html |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Last lament for true braveheart |last=Cramb |first=Auslan |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |location=London |date=20 April 2001}}</ref>\n\nBaxter was free of the [[Sectarianism in Glasgow|sectarianism]] that marked the rivalry between [[Glasgow]]'s two leading teams. His close friends included the Celtic players [[Billy McNeill]], [[Pat Crerand]] and [[Mike Jackson (footballer)|Mike Jackson]], in defiance of the unwritten rule that rivals did not associate.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/scotland/article2652410.ece |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Firm pals who broke the Glasgow mould |work=[[The Sunday Times]] |last=Baillie |first=Rodger |location=London |date=14 October 2007}}</ref>\n\nLike some other British football stars of the late 20th century, Baxter drank to excess,<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /><ref name=\"MudSweatBeers\">{{cite book |title=Mud, Sweat and Beers: A Cultural History of Sport and Alcohol |last1=Collins |first1=Tony |last2=Vamplew |first2=Wray |publisher=Berg Publishers |year=2002 |isbn=1-85973-558-4 |chapter=A Little of What Does You Good? |page=[https://archive.org/details/mudsweatbeerscul0000coll/page/104 104] |url=https://archive.org/details/mudsweatbeerscul0000coll |url-access=registration |quote=jim baxter football rangers. |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref> and at one point was said to be consuming three bottles of [[Bacardi]] a day.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> Scotland teammate [[Dave Mackay (footballer born 1934)|Dave Mackay]] unsuccessfully advised him to train harder and live more sensibly.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /> Baxter often got falling-down drunk the night before a match, but this did not seem to hamper his play, and team managers took little notice of his drinking.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /> After retiring from football Baxter became a [[pub]] licensee, an unsuitable career for a problem drinker.<ref name=\"MudSweatBeers\" /> At the age of 55 he needed two [[liver]] [[organ transplant|transplants]] in four days,<ref name=\"GuardianObit\" /><ref name=\"MudSweatBeers\" /> and promised to quit drinking.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" />\n\nHis other lifelong addiction was gambling, at which he lost \u00a3500,000 by his own estimate and \u00a3250,000 by third-party estimates.<ref name=\"GuardianObit\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/apr/16/guardianobituaries.football |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Jim Baxter |last=Glenn |first=Patrick |date=16 April 2001 |work=[[The Guardian]]  |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> Later in his life, when asked if earning the huge incomes of footballers in later decades would have made a difference, he replied, \"Aye, I would have gambled \u00a350,000 a week on the horses instead of \u00a3100.\" <ref name=\"BBCStatue\" />\n\nIn February 2001, Baxter was diagnosed as suffering from [[cancer]] of the [[pancreas]], and he died at his home on Glasgow's [[Glasgow#South Side|South Side]] on 14 April 2001, with his partner Norma and his sons Alan and Steven at his bedside.<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\" /> His funeral was held in [[Glasgow Cathedral]], where a reading was given by [[Gordon Brown]], a long-time fan of [[Raith Rovers F.C.]], where Baxter began his career.<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph2001TrueBraveheart\" />\n\n==Style of play==\nBaxter is generally regarded as one of Scotland's greatest ever players.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /> He was noted for accurate passes, for sending opponents the wrong way with a swivel of his hips, and for inspiring teammates with his confident approach.<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph2001TrueBraveheart\" /> He attracted attention by his stylish play, controlling the game with \"unhurried artistry\". He refused to conform with the \"efficient\" style that dominated British football or the energetic, physical style that was typical of Rangers at the time.<ref name=\"Holt1990SportAndBritish\" /> Indeed, although Rangers insisted that players tuck their shirts completely into their shorts, Baxter always let part of his dangle over his left hip.<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0,,5~1561270,00.html | accessdate=15 April 2009 | title=Jim Baxter | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822193123/http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/halloffame/0%2C%2C5~1561270%2C00.html | archivedate=22 August 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He described his approach to playing football as \"treating the ball like a woman. Give it a cuddle, caress it a wee bit, take your time, and you'll get the required response\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Football Talk: The Language & Folklore of the World's Greatest Game |last=Seddon |first=Peter |publisher=Robson |year=2004 |isbn=1-86105-683-4 |chapter=Nothing but a Bag of Wind? |page=49 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7N3iYWotTPYC&pg=PA49&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPP7,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nBaxter played most of his best football in his early twenties, before the leg fracture against [[Rapid Vienna]] in December 1964 and the start of his heavy drinking that made his nickname \"Slim Jim\" less appropriate.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = http://sport.scotsman.com/top-stories/Flawed-legend--and-greater.2251226.jp |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Flawed legend - and greater for it |last=Pattullo |first=Alan |work=[[The Scotsman]] }}</ref>\nHe was also noted as a joker on the pitch.<ref name=\"IndependentObit\" /> After the [[replay (sports)|replay]] of the [[Scottish Cup]] Final against Celtic in 1963 he stuffed the match ball up his shirt and later gave it to a new member of the team. The [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] insisted that the ball should be returned, and Rangers sent them a ball, but possibly not the match ball.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/2008/12/22/night-slim-jim-had-a-ball-86908-20989029/ |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Night Slim Jim Had A Ball |date=22 December 2008 |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]}}</ref> Most famously, during Scotland's 3\u20132 win over England in 1967, he taunted his opponents by playing \"[[keepie uppie]]\" during the game.<ref name=\"Holt1990SportAndBritish\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Jim Baxter statue Hill Of Beath.jpg|thumb|Statue in Baxter's honour in his home town, [[Hill of Beath]] in [[Fife]] \u2013 with the ball on his famous left foot]]\n[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] manager [[Alex Ferguson]] described Baxter as \"arguably the best player to play in Scottish football\"<ref name=\"DailyTelgraphObit\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3003288/Baxter-best-to-play-in-Scottish-football.html | accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Baxter 'best to play in Scottish football' |last=Gray |first=William |date=15 April 2001 |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |location=London}}</ref> and \"the greatest player I ever played with&nbsp;... He had touch, balance, vision and just this wonderful aura&nbsp;...\" Rangers manager [[Willie Waddell]] said, \"Jim was the finest [[left half]] ever produced by Rangers.\" [[Jimmy Johnstone]], who played for Rangers' great rivals Celtic, said shortly after Baxter's death, \"He was a great man and a genius on the ball.\"<ref name=\"SundayMirror15Apr2001\">{{cite news |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |date=15 April 2001 |last=McGill |first=Craig |title=Slim Jim Baxter 1939 - 2001: Death of a Legend |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/SLIM+JIM+BAXTER+1939+-+2001%3A+DEATH+OF+A+LEGEND%3B+He+was+one+of+the...-a073218048 |accessdate=10 October 2017}}</ref> Allegedly [[Pel\u00e9]] once said that Baxter should have been a [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian]].<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /> After Baxter's performance in the 1963 \"rest of the world\" vs England match, [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]] asked, \"Where has this fellow been hiding?\"<ref name=\"IndependentSelfconfidentMaster\" /> Shortly before his own death, [[George Best]] named Baxter as one of the best eleven players he had played with or against in an interview with [[FourFourTwo]] magazine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/george-best-perfect-xi |title=George Best: Perfect XI |last=Massarella |first=Louis |date=December 2005 |website=Four Four Two |accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nBaxter is a member of the Rangers supporters' Hall of Fame,<ref name=\"RangersHOFBaxter\" /> and one of the first 50 added to the Scottish Sporting Hall of Fame when it was created in 2002.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/2530435.stm |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Scotland honours sporting legends |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=30 November 2002}}</ref><ref name=SSHOF>{{cite web|url=http://www.sshf.co.uk/inductees/a-f/jim-baxter/|title=Scottish Sports Hall of Fame: Jim Baxter|publisher=[[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame]]|date=|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> In 2004, he was also inducted into the [[Scottish Football Hall of Fame]].<ref name=SHOF>{{cite web |url=http://scottishfootballhalloffame.co.uk/jim-baxter/ |title=Scottish Football Hall of Fame - Jim Baxter|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> In the December 1999 issue of [[World Soccer (magazine)|World Soccer magazine]] he was voted by a readers' poll into a list of the [[World Soccer (magazine)#The Greatest Players of the 20th century|100 greatest players of the 20th century]].<ref>{{cite web|title=World Soccer Players of the Century (2001)|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamHons/HonsWldSocPlyrsCent.html|website=England Football Online|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Tartan Army]] unsuccessfully attempted to get the new [[Wembley Stadium]] footbridge named after him,<ref>{{cite book \n| title=The Unofficial Football World Championships: An Alternative Soccer History |last=Brown |first=Paul |publisher=Tonto Books |year=2006|isbn=0-9552183-1-4 |chapter=Classic Matches |page=74 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XktTup3O-fQC&pg=PA74&dq=jim+baxter+football+rangers#PPA5,M1 |accessdate=5 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lda.gov.uk/server/show/ConWebDoc.1071 |accessdate=6 January 2008 |title=Battle of the bridge commences |publisher=London Development Agency |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050518091028/http://www.lda.gov.uk/server/show/ConWebDoc.1071 |archivedate=18 May 2005  }}</ref> and on 24 February 2005 [[Scottish National Party]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] [[Pete Wishart]] presented an [[Early Day Motion]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] supporting this campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.currybet.net/cbet_blog/2005/03/baxter_vs_moore.php |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Baxter vs Moore - Costing you money in Parliament }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westminster.snp.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1378&Itemid=40 |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=SNP MP's motion backs Jim Baxter bridge at Wembley |publisher=[[Scottish National Party]] |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070620025818/http://www.westminster.snp.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1378&Itemid=40 |archivedate=20 June 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, a statue of Baxter was erected in his birthplace, [[Hill of Beath]] in [[Fife]], after a campaign that raised \u00a380,000.<ref name=\"BlackCatalogue\" /><ref name=\"BBCStatue\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2962041.stm |accessdate=5 January 2009 |title=Statue to football legend unveiled |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=20 April 2003 }}</ref> Fellow footballer and midfielder  [[Scott Brown (footballer, born June 1985)|Scott Brown]], who would become Scotland captain in the 2010s, was also raised in the village and attended the same school, with the Baxter statue across the street from his childhood home,<ref name=Brown>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/top-football-stories/slim-jim-watching-over-hibs-kid-scott-1-878028|title=Slim Jim watching over Hibs kid Scott|work=The Scotsman|first=David|last=Hardie|date=6 May 2003|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref> although Brown chose to sign for Celtic rather than Rangers.<ref name=\"Guardian 16May2007\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/may/16/newsstory.sport6|title=Celtic bag Brown from under Rangers' nose|work=The Guardian |first=Mark |last=Atkinson |date=16 May 2007|accessdate=6 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International appearances===\n:Sources:<ref name=NFT/><ref name=fsscot/><ref name=SFA/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1960||1||0\n|-\n|1961||7||0\n|-\n|1962||4||1\n|-\n|1963||7||2\n|-\n|1964||5||0\n|-\n|1965||3||0\n|-\n|1966||4||0\n|-\n|1967||3||0\n|-\n!Total||34||3\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Scotland's goal tally first.''<ref name=NFT>{{NFT|18038|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=fsscot>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotland/player.php?playerid=739|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Scotland|work=Fitbastats|date=|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=SFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=2492&playerid=112900|title=Jim Baxter profile|publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]] |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 2 May 1962 || [[Hampden Park]], [[Glasgow]] || {{fb|URU}} || 1\u20133 || 2\u20133 || [[Exhibition game|Friendly]]\n|-\n| 2.\n| rowspan=2 | 6 April 1963 || rowspan=2 | [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]], [[London]] || rowspan=2 | {{fb|ENG}} || 1\u20130 || rowspan=2 | 2\u20131 || rowspan=2 | [[1963 British Home Championship]]\n|-\n| 3.\n| 2\u20130\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Rangers'''\n*[[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] Runner-up: [[1960\u201361 European Cup Winners' Cup|1960\u201361]]<ref name=fs60161>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=6|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1960\u201361|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[List of Scottish football champions#Scottish League First Division (1893\u20131975)|Scottish League First Division]]: [[1960\u201361 Scottish First Division|1960\u201361]],<ref name=fs60161/> [[1962\u201363 Scottish First Division|1962\u201363]],<ref name=fs6263>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=4|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1962\u201363|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> [[1963\u201364 Scottish First Division|1963\u201364]]<ref name=fs6364>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=3|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1963\u201364|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> \n*[[Scottish Cup]]: [[1961\u201362 Scottish Cup|1961\u201362]],<ref name=fs6162>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=5|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1961\u201362|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref> [[1962\u201363 Scottish Cup|1962\u201363]],<ref name=fs6263/> [[1963\u201364 Scottish Cup|1963\u201364]]<ref name=fs6364/>\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[1960\u201361 Scottish League Cup|1960\u201361]],<ref name=fs60161/> [[1961\u201362 Scottish League Cup|1961\u201362]],<ref name=fs6162/> [[1963\u201364 Scottish League Cup|1963\u201364]],<ref name=fs6364/> [[1964\u201365 Scottish League Cup|1964\u201365]]<ref name=fs6465>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/rangers/player_games.php?playerid=1474&page=2|title=Matches played by Jim Baxter for Rangers, 1964\u201365|work=Fitbastats |accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Scottish Football Hall of Fame]] (inaugural inductee)<ref name=SHOF/>\n*[[Scottish Sports Hall of Fame#Football|Scottish Sports Hall of Fame]] (inaugural inductee)<ref name=SSHOF/>\n*[[Ballon d'Or]]: [[1965 Ballon d'Or|1965]] (13th place)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy65.html |title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1965 |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=22 June 2005 |accessdate=24 October 2016 |first=Pierrend |last=Jos\u00e9 Luis}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{SFA profile}}\n* [http://www.glasgowguide.co.uk/images_jbf1.html  Jim Baxter's Funeral Images @ Glasgow Guide]\n* {{NeilBrownPlayers|player/jimbaxter}}\n\n{{Rangers F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{Scottish Football Hall of Fame}}\n{{Raith Rovers F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baxter, Jim}}\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:People from Hill of Beath]]\n[[Category:People educated at Beath High School]]\n[[Category:Raith Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Black Watch soldiers]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League representative players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fife]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-23 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Crossgates Primrose F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Junior Football Association players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Royals players]]\n[[Category:United Soccer Association players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Association football wing halves]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Baxter"}
{"title_page": "Las Pozas", "text_new": "[[File:Xilitla Las Pozas 0407 104.jpg|thumb|200px]]\n[[File:Xilitla Las Pozas 0407 036.jpg|thumb|The surrealist sculpture park ''Las Pozas'', Xilitla]]\n\n'''Las Pozas''' (\"the Pools\") is a surrealistic group of structures created by [[Edward James]], more than {{convert|2000|ft|m}} above sea level, in a subtropical rainforest in the mountains of [[Mexico]]. It includes more than {{convert|80|acre|ha}} of natural waterfalls and pools interlaced with towering surrealist sculptures in concrete.<ref name=\"NYT-30Mar08\">[https://www.nytimes.com/indexes/2008/03/30/style/t/index.html#pageName=30laspozas \"Dream Works: Can a Legendary Surrealist Garden in Mexico Bloom Again?\"], ''New York Times Style Magazine'', 30 March 2008</ref>\n\nLas Pozas is near the village of [[Xilitla, San Luis Potos\u00ed]], a seven-hour drive north of Mexico City. In the early 1940s, James went to [[Los Angeles, California]], and then decided that he \"wanted a Garden of Eden set up . . . and I saw that Mexico was far more romantic\" and had \"far more room than there is in crowded Southern California\".<ref>Margaret Hooks, [http://www.edwardjameslaspozas.com \"Surreal Eden: Edward James & Las Pozas\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525093007/http://edwardjameslaspozas.com/ |date=2017-05-25 }}, Princeton Architectural Press, New York, 2006, {{ISBN|978-1-56898-612-8}}</ref> In Hollywood in 1941, his lifetime friend and cousin, [[Magic Realism|Magic Realist]] painter [[Bridget Bate Tichenor]], encouraged him to search for a surreal location in Mexico to express his diverse esoteric interests.<ref>[http://BridgetBateTichenor.com/ Bridget Bate Tichenor Biography]</ref> In [[Cuernavaca, Mexico|Cuernavaca]], he hired Plutarco Gastelum as a guide. They came to know Xilitla in November 1945.<ref name=\"NYT-30Mar08\"/> Eventually, Plutarco got married and had four children. James was \"Uncle Edward\" to the children and frequently stayed with them in a house Plutarco had built, a mock-Gothic cement castle, now a hotel \u2013 La Posada El Castillo.<ref name=\"L&T\"/>\n\nBetween 1949 and 1984, James built scores of surreal concrete structures which carry the names ''The House on Three Floors Which Will in Fact Have Five or Four or Six'', ''The House with a Roof like a Whale'', and ''The Staircase to Heaven''.<ref name=\"L&T\">Gini Alhadeff, [http://www.travelandleisure.com/articles/concrete-jungle \"Concrete Jungle\"], ''Travel + Leisure\", September 2003</ref> There were also plantings and beds full of tropical plants, including orchids \u2014 there were, apparently, 29,000 at Las Pozas at one time<ref name=\"TG-6Nov07\">Joanna Moorhead, [http://arts.guardian.co.uk/art/architecture/story/0,,2206530,00.html \"The Magic Kingdom (James' Las Pozas, Mexico)\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 November 2007</ref> \u2014 and a variety of small homes, niches, and pens that held exotic birds and wild animals from the world over\u2014James owned many exotic animals and once even took his pet boa constrictors to the Hotel Francis in [[Mexico City]].<ref name=\"L&T\"/>\n\nMassive sculptures up to four stories tall punctuate the site. The many trails throughout the garden site are composed of steps, ramps, bridges and narrow, winding walkways that traverse the valley walls.<ref>[http://www.stepsandfalls.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=28 \"Los Pozas \u2013 steps and falls\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080416080547/http://www.stepsandfalls.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=28 |date=2008-04-16 }}, virtual tour of the grounds of Las Pozas, DVD, published 2007; retrieved 30 March 2008</ref> Construction of Las Pozas cost more than $5 million. To pay for it, James sold his collection of surrealistic art at an auction.<ref name=\"L&T\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 2007, the Fundaci\u00f3n Pedro y Elena Hern\u00e1ndez, the company [[Cemex]], and the government of [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]] paid about $2.2 million for Las Pozas and created [http://www.xilitla.org Fondo Xilitla], a foundation that oversees the preservation and restoration of the site.<ref name=\"NYT-30Mar08\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Las Pozas de Xilitla}}\n*[http://www.laspozasxilitla.org.mx/en/  Official '''Las Pozas'''  website] \u2014 ''info + images + media + resources''.\n*[http://www.archdaily.com/790389/inside-las-pozas-edward-james-surrealist-garden-in-the-mexican-jungle    Archdaily.com:   \"Inside Las Pozas, Edward James' Surrealist Garden in the Mexican Jungle\"] \u2014 ''with photos''.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0oosdgHLTGY YouTube.com:  \"The Secret Life of Edward James\" \u2014  1975 biographic video by George Melly (54 minutes)]\n*[http://www.pedroyelena.org/  Fundaci\u00f3n Pedro y Elena Hern\u00e1ndez website].\n\n\n\n\n{{coord|21.3970|N|98.9970|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pozas, Las}}\n[[Category:Gardens in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Visionary environments]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in San Luis Potos\u00ed]]\n[[Category:Concrete sculptures]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Sculpture gardens, trails and parks in North America]]\n[[Category:Surrealist works]]\n[[Category:History of San Luis Potos\u00ed]]\n[[Category:Landscape design history]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in San Luis Potos\u00ed]]\n[[Category:1949 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:1949 in arts]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Xilitla Las Pozas 0407 104.jpg|thumb|200px]]\n[[File:Xilitla Las Pozas 0407 036.jpg|thumb|The surrealist sculpture park ''Las Pozas'', Xilitla]]\n\n'''Las PoZas''' (\"the Pools\") is a surrealistic group of structures created by [[Edward James]], more than {{convert|2000|ft|m}} above sea level, in a subtropical rainforest in the mountains of [[Mexico]]. It includes more than {{convert|80|acre|ha}} of natural waterfalls and pools interlaced with towering surrealist sculptures in concrete.<ref name=\"NYT-30Mar08\">[https://www.nytimes.com/indexes/2008/03/30/style/t/index.html#pageName=30laspozas \"Dream Works: Can a Legendary Surrealist Garden in Mexico Bloom Again?\"], ''New York Times Style Magazine'', 30 March 2008</ref>\n\nLas Pozas is near the village of [[Xilitla, San Luis Potos\u00ed]], a seven-hour drive north of Mexico City. In the early 1940s, James went to [[Los Angeles, California]], and then decided that he \"wanted a Garden of Eden set up . . . and I saw that Mexico was far more romantic\" and had \"far more room than there is in crowded Southern California\".<ref>Margaret Hooks, [http://www.edwardjameslaspozas.com \"Surreal Eden: Edward James & Las Pozas\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525093007/http://edwardjameslaspozas.com/ |date=2017-05-25 }}, Princeton Architectural Press, New York, 2006, {{ISBN|978-1-56898-612-8}}</ref> In Hollywood in 1941, his lifetime friend and cousin, [[Magic Realism|Magic Realist]] painter [[Bridget Bate Tichenor]], encouraged him to search for a surreal location in Mexico to express his diverse esoteric interests.<ref>[http://BridgetBateTichenor.com/ Bridget Bate Tichenor Biography]</ref> In [[Cuernavaca, Mexico|Cuernavaca]], he hired Plutarco Gastelum as a guide. They came to know Xilitla in November 1945.<ref name=\"NYT-30Mar08\"/> Eventually, Plutarco got married and had four children. James was \"Uncle Edward\" to the children and frequently stayed with them in a house Plutarco had built, a mock-Gothic cement castle, now a hotel \u2013 La Posada El Castillo.<ref name=\"L&T\"/>\n\nBetween 1949 and 1984, James built scores of surreal concrete structures which carry the names ''The House on Three Floors Which Will in Fact Have Five or Four or Six'', ''The House with a Roof like a Whale'', and ''The Staircase to Heaven''.<ref name=\"L&T\">Gini Alhadeff, [http://www.travelandleisure.com/articles/concrete-jungle \"Concrete Jungle\"], ''Travel + Leisure\", September 2003</ref> There were also plantings and beds full of tropical plants, including orchids \u2014 there were, apparently, 29,000 at Las Pozas at one time<ref name=\"TG-6Nov07\">Joanna Moorhead, [http://arts.guardian.co.uk/art/architecture/story/0,,2206530,00.html \"The Magic Kingdom (James' Las Pozas, Mexico)\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 November 2007</ref> \u2014 and a variety of small homes, niches, and pens that held exotic birds and wild animals from the world over\u2014James owned many exotic animals and once even took his pet boa constrictors to the Hotel Francis in [[Mexico City]].<ref name=\"L&T\"/>\n\nMassive sculptures up to four stories tall punctuate the site. The many trails throughout the garden site are composed of steps, ramps, bridges and narrow, winding walkways that traverse the valley walls.<ref>[http://www.stepsandfalls.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=28 \"Los Pozas \u2013 steps and falls\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080416080547/http://www.stepsandfalls.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=28 |date=2008-04-16 }}, virtual tour of the grounds of Las Pozas, DVD, published 2007; retrieved 30 March 2008</ref> Construction of Las Pozas cost more than $5 million. To pay for it, James sold his collection of surrealistic art at an auction.<ref name=\"L&T\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 2007, the Fundaci\u00f3n Pedro y Elena Hern\u00e1ndez, the company [[Cemex]], and the government of [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]] paid about $2.2 million for Las Pozas and created [http://www.xilitla.org Fondo Xilitla], a foundation that oversees the preservation and restoration of the site.<ref name=\"NYT-30Mar08\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Las Pozas de Xilitla}}\n*[http://www.laspozasxilitla.org.mx/en/  Official '''Las Pozas'''  website] \u2014 ''info + images + media + resources''.\n*[http://www.archdaily.com/790389/inside-las-pozas-edward-james-surrealist-garden-in-the-mex