m/ew/gallery/0,,20593459_20820828,00.html|title=TV Season Finale Awards: YOUR 2014 Winners|date=May 28, 2014|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref>\n| Best Non-Romantic Cliffhanger\n| rowspan=\"6\"| \"Berlin (No. 8) Conclusion\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Funniest Moment in a Drama\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Weakest/Most Divisive Twist\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Final Shot\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Most Likely to Earn Someone an Emmy Nomination\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Biggest Regret That I Didn't See It, I Just Heard or Read About It\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[66th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| Outstanding Stunt Coordination for a Drama Series, Miniseries, or Movie\n| ''The Blacklist''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers Awards|ASCAP Film and Television Music Awards]]\n| Top TV Series\n| ''The Blacklist'' (Dave Porter)\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[40th Saturn Awards|Saturn Award]]\n| Best Network Television Series Release\n| ''The Blacklist''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Actor in a Television Series\n| James Spader\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/2015_72nd_Golden_Globes_Nominees |title=2015 Golden Globe Nominations |publisher=The Hollywood Foreign Press Association |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141212145440/http://www.goldenglobes.com/2015_72nd_Golden_Globes_Nominees |archivedate=December 12, 2014 }}</ref>\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actor -Television Series Drama]]\n| [[James Spader]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[67th Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| [[Alan Alda]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| [[68th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| Outstanding Stunt Coordination for a Drama Series, Miniseries, or Movie\n| ''The Blacklist''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Screen Actors Guild Awards\n| Outstanding Action Performance by a Stunt Ensemble in a Television Series\n| stunt cast{{ref|1|note 1}}\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| People's Choice Awards\n| Favorite TV Crime Drama\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''The Blacklist''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[69th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| Outstanding Stunt Coordination for a Drama Series, Miniseries, or Movie\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n;Note:\n{{refbegin}}\n#{{note|1}}The stunt cast included Airon Armstrong, Kevin Ball, Chris Barnes, Nitasha Bhambree, Michael C. Brennan, Bryce Burke, Jared Burke, Kachina Dechert, Neimah Djourabchi, Paul Drechsler-Martell, Stefanie Flores, Edward Gabree, Christopher Jon Gombos, Tony Guida, Gene Harrison, Greg Harvey, Chad Hessler, Cort Hessler, Donald John Hewitt, Scott Kelly, Pete Klein, Drew Leary, Luke Lesko, Roberto Lopez, Terence Lorino, Stephen Mann, Michael Matera, Chazz Menendez, Luis Moco, Declan Mulvey, James Newman, Josiah Nolan, Christopher Parker, Ashley Pynn, Jodi Michelle Pynn, Bob Roseman, Akos Schenek, Hannah Scott, Derrick Simmons, Brian Smyj, Matt Triplett, Thad Turner, and Aaron Vexler.\n{{refend}}\n\n==Other media==\n\n===Comics===\n[[Titan Books]] released an official comic book series based on the series, written by Nicole Phillips and drawn by Beni Lobel. The series' crew is working in the project as well.\n\nEditor David Leach told ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' that the comic is \"a true extension of the television series\" giving \"new dimensions of the characters that have captured the audiences worldwide\". The series will open with a six-issue story arc, which will be \"a journey deep into the dark world of international espionage, conspiracies and intrigue on a global scale\".\n\nIssue #1 was launched July 22, 2015, in both comic book and digital stores.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McMillan |first=Graeme |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/nbcs-blacklist-coming-comics-summer-788693 |title=NBC's 'The Blacklist' Coming to Comics This Summer|date=April 14, 2015 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=April 14, 2015|quote=David Leach, who'll edit the new monthly series, called the comic book 'a true extension of the television series['], promising a glimpse at 'new dimensions of the characters that have captured the audiences worldwide.{{'-}}}}</ref>\n\n=== Games ===\nA mobile game by [[Gameloft]] based on the series, ''The Blacklist: Conspiracy'', was released on June 23, 2016, for Android, iOS and Windows devices.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/gameloft-launches-the-blacklist-conspiracy-for-smartphones-and-tablets-584146551.html|title=Gameloft Launches \"The Blacklist: Conspiracy\" for Smartphones and Tablets|publisher=Gameloft|via=PR Newswire|language=en|access-date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> The game consists of the player as a member of the task force. Players can interact with Reddington and Cooper, other members of the task force, as well as interrogate potential suspects and witnesses. The game mainly consists of searching for missing items in different environments, as well as mini games to further the investigations. Players can also make decisions that alter the route of the story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gameloft.com/en/game/blacklist|title=The Blacklist|website=www.gameloft.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref>\n\n===Spin-off===\n{{main|The Blacklist: Redemption}}\n\nIn March 2016, NBC began developing a spin-off series created by Bokenkamp and Eisendrath, who would also serve as executive producers with Davis and Fox. The project was set to star [[Famke Janssen]] as Susan \"Scottie\" Hargrave (formerly ''Halsted'') and Eggold, in his role as Tom Keen, as well as [[Edi Gathegi]] reprising his role as Matias Solomon. [[Tawny Cypress]] was cast as Nez Rowan, a character already recurring during the third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/the-blacklist-spinoff-tawny-cypress-cast-1201728743/ |title='The Blacklist' Spinoff: Tawny Cypress Cast |website= Deadline.com}}</ref> Hargrave first appeared on ''The Blacklist'' episode \"Susan Hargrave\", with \"Alexander Kirk\" serving as a [[backdoor pilot]] for the potential series. That episode was written by Bokenkamp and Eisendrath and directed by Michael Dinner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/the-blacklist-spinoff-famke-janssen-star-nbc-1201728137/|title='The Blacklist' Spinoff Starring Famke Janssen In the Works At NBC|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 29, 2016|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> On May 14, 2016, a pilot for the series, ''The Blacklist: Redemption'', was ordered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/05/the-blacklist-redemption-spinoff-series-nbc-title-1201755724/|title='The Blacklist' Spinoff Picked Up To Series By NBC, Gets Title|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|website=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref> The series was canceled after one season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/the-blacklist-redemption-canceled-nbc-one-season-1202091823/|title='The Blacklist: Redemption' Canceled By NBC After One Season|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=May 12, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref> Eggold continued his role on ''The Blacklist''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/ryan-eggold-rejoin-the-blacklist-season-5-series-regular-redemption-cancellation-1202091847/|title=Ryan Eggold To Rejoin 'The Blacklist' As Series Regular Following 'Redemption' Cancellation|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=May 12, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.nbc.com/the-blacklist}}\n* {{IMDb title|2741602|The Blacklist}}\n\n{{sequence\n|prev=''[[New Girl]]''<br />[[Super Bowl XLVIII|2014]]\n|list=[[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|Super Bowl lead-out program]]<br />''The Blacklist''<br />[[Super Bowl XLIX|2015]]\n|next=''[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]''<br />[[Super Bowl 50|2016]]\n}}\n{{The Blacklist}}\n{{NBCNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n{{Portal bar|Television|United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blacklist, The}}\n[[Category:The Blacklist (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American action television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation in fiction]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Terrorism in television]]\n[[Category:Crime thriller television series]]\n[[Category:American spy thriller television series]]\n[[Category:Espionage television series]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American crime thriller television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Blacklist\n| image                = Blacklist Title Card.jpg\n| caption              = \n| show_name_2          = \n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Crime drama]]\n* [[Action film|Action]]<ref name=press/>\n* [[Thriller film|Thriller]]\n* [[Mystery film|Mystery]]\n}}\n| creator              = [[Jon Bokenkamp]]\n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n| director             = \n| creative_director    = \n| presenter            = \n| starring             = {{Plain list |\n* [[James Spader]]\n* [[Megan Boone]]\n* [[Diego Klattenhoff]]\n* [[Ryan Eggold]]\n* [[Parminder Nagra]]\n* [[Harry Lennix]]\n* [[Amir Arison]]\n* [[Mozhan Marn\u00f2]]\n* [[Hisham Tawfiq]]\n}}\n| judges               = \n| voices               = \n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = {{Plain list |\n*[[Dave Porter (composer)|Dave Porter]]\n*[[James S. Levine]]\n}}\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 7\n| num_episodes         = <onlyinclude>147</onlyinclude>\n| list_episodes        = List of The Blacklist episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plain list |\n* [[Jon Bokenkamp]]\n* [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]]\n* [[John Eisendrath]]\n* John Fox\n* [[Joe Carnahan]]\n* [[James Spader]]\n}}\n| producer             = [[Anthony Sparks]]\n| editor               = \n| location             = [[New York City]]\n| cinematography       = {{Plain list |\n* [[Frank Prinzi]]\n* [[Arthur Albert]]\n* Michael Caracciolo\n* Yasu Tanida\n}}\n| camera               = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime              = 45 minutes\n| company              = {{Plain list |\n* [[Davis Entertainment]]\n* [[Universal Television]]\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n* Open 4 Business Productions\n}}\n| distributor          = {{Plain list |\n*[[Sony Pictures Television]]\n* [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]]\n}}\n| channel              = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format       = [[576i]] [[SDTV]]<br />[[1080i]] [[HDTV]]<br />[[4K resolution|4K]] [[UHDTV]] (2016\u2013)\n| audio_format         = \n| first_run            = \n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2013|9|23}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|present}}\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = ''[[The Blacklist: Redemption]]''\n| related              = \n| website              = http://www.nbc.com/the-blacklist\n| website_title        = Official website\n| production_website   = \n}}\n\n'''''The Blacklist''''' is an American [[crime thriller]] television series that premiered on [[NBC]] on September 23, 2013. The show follows Raymond \"Red\" Reddington ([[James Spader]]), a former [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] officer turned high-profile criminal, who voluntarily surrenders to the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] after eluding capture for decades. He tells the FBI that he has a list of the most dangerous criminals in the world that he has compiled over the years and is willing to inform on their operations in exchange for [[Legal immunity|immunity from prosecution]]. However, he insists on working exclusively with a rookie FBI [[criminal profiler|profiler]] by the name of Elizabeth Keen ([[Megan Boone]]). \n\nThe series also stars [[Diego Klattenhoff]], [[Ryan Eggold]] and [[Harry Lennix]]. The pilot episode was written by [[Jon Bokenkamp]] and directed by [[Joe Carnahan]].<ref name=press>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/05/12/nbc-reveals-its-2013-14-primetime-schedule-840010/20130512nbc03/ |title=NBC Reveals Its 2013\u201314 Primetime Schedule |date=May 12, 2013 |website=The Futon Critic |accessdate=May 19, 2013}}</ref> Executive producers for the series include Bokenkamp, [[John Eisendrath]] and [[John Davis (producer)|John Davis]] for [[Sony Pictures Television]], [[Universal Television]] and [[Davis Entertainment]].\n\nEach season has received positive reviews,<ref name=\"Wiegand\">{{cite news|last=Wiegand|first=David|title=Suspense dramas 'Blacklist,' 'Hostages' to premiere|url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Suspense-dramas-Blacklist-Hostages-to-4825782.php|accessdate=May 22, 2015|newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Jensen|first=Jeff|title=The Blacklist Review|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20743635,00.html|accessdate=December 30, 2013|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 12, 2013}}</ref> with many critics praising Spader's performance in particular.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ostrow|first=Joanne|title=Review: James Spader in \"The Blacklist\" on NBC|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/ostrow/2013/09/06/review-james-spader-in-the-blacklist-on-nbc/16211/|accessdate=December 30, 2013|date=September 6, 2013|newspaper=[[The Denver Post]]}}</ref> On March 11, 2019, NBC renewed the series for a seventh season,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-blacklist-renewed-season-7-nbc-original-cast-return-1202573021/ |title='The Blacklist' Renewed For Season 7 By NBC With Original Cast Set To Return |work=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=March 11, 2019 |accessdate=March 11, 2019}}</ref> which premiered on October 4, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/nbc-fall-premiere-dates-2019-the-voice-chicago-bluff-city-law-sunnyside-perfect-harmony-1202633630/|title=NBC Fall Premiere Dates: \u2018The Voice\u2019, \u2018This Is Us\u2019, New \u2018Bluff City Law\u2019 & \u2018Sunnyside\u2019, More|work=Deadline Hollywood|first=Erik|last=Pederson|date=June 17, 2019|accessdate=June 17, 2019}}</ref> On February 20, 2020, NBC renewed the series for an eighth season.<ref name=\"Blacklist Renewed\">{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=\u2018The Blacklist\u2019 Renewed For Season 8 By NBC|url=https://deadline.com/2020/02/the-blacklist-renewed-season-8-nbc-season-7-return-date-1202863926/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 20, 2020|accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nRaymond \"Red\" Reddington, a former [[Office of Naval Intelligence|US Naval Intelligence]] officer who had disappeared twenty years earlier to become one of the FBI's [[FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives|Ten Most Wanted Fugitives]], surrenders himself to FBI Assistant Director Harold Cooper at the [[J. Edgar Hoover Building]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]. Taken to an FBI \"[[black site]]\", Reddington claims he wishes to help the FBI track down and apprehend the criminals and terrorists he spent the last twenty years associating with; individuals that are so dangerous and devious that the United States government is unaware of their very existence.\n\nHe offers Cooper his knowledge and assistance on two conditions: immunity from prosecution, and that he wants to work exclusively with Elizabeth Keen, a rookie [[offender profiling|profiler]] newly assigned to Cooper. Keen and Cooper are suspicious of Reddington's interest in her, but he will only say that she is \"very special\". After Cooper tests Reddington's offer in locating and killing a terrorist in the first episode, Reddington reveals that this man was only the first on his \"blacklist\" of global criminals, which he has compiled over his criminal career, and states that he and the FBI have a mutual interest in eliminating them. The mysteries of Reddington's and Liz's lives, and his interest in her, are gradually revealed as the series progresses. Each episode features one of the global criminals, and Reddington assisting the team tracking and apprehending them. The rank and name or alias of the featured criminal on the list is displayed at the start of every episode, with a few exceptions.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of The Blacklist characters}}\n\n* [[James Spader]] as Raymond \"Red\" Reddington: A master criminal turned [[confidential informant]] for the [[FBI]], later revealed to be Elizabeth Keen's biological father. However, it is revealed during the course of seasons 5 and 6 that he is an impostor who had the real Reddington killed and kept his bones in a suitcase.\n* [[Megan Boone]] as Elizabeth \"Liz\" Keen: Born Masha Rostova, Keen is a special agent and profiler with the FBI on Harold Cooper's team.\n* [[Diego Klattenhoff]] as Donald Ressler: A special agent with the FBI on Cooper's team, who also became the Acting Assistant Director of the [[FBI Counterterrorism Division]].\n* [[Ryan Eggold]] as Tom Keen: Born Christopher Hargrave, later taking the adoptive name Jacob Phelps, Keen works as a [[covert operative]] and is Liz's husband (seasons 1\u20135).\n* [[Parminder Nagra]] as Meera Malik: A [[field agent]] with the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] who worked with Cooper's FBI team (season 1).\n* [[Harry Lennix]] as Harold Cooper: The Assistant Director of the FBI Counterterrorism Division who uses Reddington to stop people on his Blacklist.\n* [[Amir Arison]] as Aram Mojtabai: A cyber expert with the FBI on Cooper's team (recurring, season 1; main, season 2\u2013present).\n* [[Mozhan Marn\u00f2]] as Samar Navabi: A [[Mossad]] agent who works with Cooper's FBI team (seasons 2\u20136).\n* [[Hisham Tawfiq]] as Dembe Zuma: Reddington's bodyguard and confidante (recurring, seasons 1\u20132; main, season 3\u2013present).\n* Laura Sohn as Alina Park: A field agent with the FBI who previously worked in [[Anchorage]] (recurring, season 7).\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of The Blacklist episodes}}\n{{:List of The Blacklist episodes}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn October 4, 2013, NBC ordered nine additional episodes, filling out the series' first season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/10/04/the-blacklist-picked-up-for-a-full-season-by-nbc/207022/|title='The Blacklist' Picked Up for a Full Season by NBC|website=[[TV by the Numbers]]|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=October 4, 2013|accessdate=October 5, 2013}}</ref> On December 3, 2013, NBC renewed the series for a 22-episode second season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/12/03/the-blacklist-renewed-by-nbc-for-second-season/219888/|title='The Blacklist' Renewed for Second Season by NBC|website=TV by the Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=December 3, 2013|accessdate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> On May 11, 2014, owing to the series' breakout success, NBC decided to air an episode in the coveted [[List of Super Bowl lead-out programs|post\u2013Super Bowl timeslot]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/05/11/nbc-fall-schedule-2014/|title=NBC reveals fall TV schedule|date=May 11, 2014|accessdate=September 5, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> On December 5, 2015, the series was renewed for a fourth season, which premiered on September 22, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Blacklist has been renewed for season 4 |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/12/07/the-blacklist-renewed-season-4|accessdate=December 7, 2015|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC Fall Premiere Dates deadline\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/06/nbc-fall-2016-premiere-dates-the-good-place-the-voice-preview-1201773358/|title=NBC Sets Fall 2016 Premiere Dates, 'The Good Place' Gets Post-'The Voice' Preview|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 15, 2016|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\nA spin-off series, ''[[The Blacklist: Redemption]]'', premiered on February 23, 2017. On May 11, 2017, the series was renewed for a fifth season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/the-blacklist-renewed-season-5-nbc-1202089541/|title='The Blacklist' Renewed For Season 5 By NBC|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=May 11, 2017 |website=Deadline}}</ref> while the spin-off was canceled the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/05/12/blacklist-redemption-canceled/|title='The Blacklist: Redemption' Canceled After One Season |date=May 12, 2017|website=EW.com}}</ref> The fifth season premiered on September 27, 2017.<ref name=\"Date change\">{{Cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2017/07/31/the-good-place-season-2-premiere-date-new-hour-long-episode/|title=NBC Tweaks Fall Rollout: Good Place Gets Early Talent-Boosted Premiere, The Blacklist Return Moved Up|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=July 31, 2017|website=TVLine|access-date=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conception===\nAfter showing a screening of [[Pilot (The Blacklist)|the pilot]] at [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]], producers revealed that their inspiration for ''The Blacklist'' came from the capture of [[Whitey Bulger]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=July 18, 2013 |title=Comic-Con: 'The Blacklist' Inspired by Whitey Bulger's Capture |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/comic-con-blacklist-inspired-by-585520 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Recalling the experience in an interview with [[Collider (website)|Collider]], executive producer [[John Eisendrath]] stated:\n\n{{cquote|So, the idea was, 'Well, what would happen if a man like Whitey Bulger turned himself in and said, \"I am here. I have some rules that I want you to follow, but if you follow them I will give you the names of people that I have worked with, during the 20 years that I have been a fugitive.{{\"'}} So, there was a real world influence that affected the shaping of the show that was already being thought about. How can you put someone that you don't trust in the center of a show about trying to find criminals? And here was an example in the real world of just such a person. It was a fortuitous turn of events, where the idea for a show was being considered, and then here comes a real life story that helped give it some shape.<ref name=\"Casting Raymond Reddington\">{{cite web |last=Radish |first=Christina |date=July 28, 2013 |title=THE BLACKLIST Showrunner John Eisendrath Talks about the Show's Inspiration, Getting Inside the Mind of a Criminal, Casting James Spader, and More |url=http://collider.com/the-blacklist-john-eisendrath-interview/ |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nNBC bought the rights to ''The Blacklist'' from [[Sony Pictures Television]] in August 2012<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=August 13, 2012 |title=ABC Buys Extended Family Comedy, NBC Goes For International Crime Drama |url=http://deadline.com/2012/08/abc-buys-extended-family-comedy-nbc-goes-for-international-crime-drama-318425/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> and [[Green-light|greenlighted]] the show in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=January 22, 2013 |title=2ND UPDATE: NBC Orders Four Drama & Three Comedy Pilots |url=http://deadline.com/2013/01/nbc-gives-pilot-order-to-crime-drama-the-blacklist-410336/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> During an NBC [[Upfront (advertising)|upfront presentation]] in May 2013, it was announced that ''The Blacklist'' was NBC's highest-testing drama in 10 years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Guthrie |first=Marisa |date=May 12, 2013 |title=TV Upfronts: Five Takeaways From NBC's Presentation |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tv-upfronts-five-takeaways-nbcs-521710 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nEisendrath said the casting process was difficult.<ref name=\"Casting Raymond Reddington\"/> In February 2013, NBC offered [[Kiefer Sutherland]] the lead role of Raymond Reddington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/kiefer_sutherlands_pilot_offer_is_more_bad_news_for_touch-2013-02|title=Kiefer Sutherland's pilot offer is more bad news for 'Touch' |last=Berkshire|first=Geoff|website=Zap2it|date=February 27, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> After considering other actors for the role, Eisendrath and Bokenkamp called [[James Spader]] to see if he would be interested in it.<ref name=\"Casting Raymond Reddington\"/> Feeling confident in Spader's understanding of the character, they cast him three days before filming began.<ref name=\"Casting Raymond Reddington\"/>\n\n[[Megan Boone]] took a week to prepare for her audition as FBI profiler Elizabeth Keen.<ref name=\"Casting Elizabeth Keen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetvaddict.com/2013/09/23/the-blacklist-intel-ep-john-eisendrath-and-megan-boone-preview-their-intriguing-new-spy-series/|title=THE BLACKLIST Intel: EP John Eisendrath and Megan Boone Preview their Intriguing New Spy Series|last=Vogt|first=Tiffany|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2015|website=The TV Addict}}</ref> Feeling like her initial audition was one of the better auditions of her career, Boone later was called back for multiple auditions.<ref name=\"Casting Elizabeth Keen\"/> In March 2013, ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' reported that Boone accepted the role as the female lead in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2013/03/megan-boone-cast-as-female-lead-in-nbc-pilot-blacklist-443384/|title=Megan Boone Cast As Female Lead In NBC Pilot 'Blacklist'|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 1, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Filming locations and technique===\nDespite being set in [[Washington, D.C.]], the series is mainly filmed in the same [[Manhattan]] studio where ''[[Law & Order]]'' was filmed for 20 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/26/james-spader-megan-boone_n_4166497.html |title=James Spader, Megan Boone Talk 'The Blacklist' |last=Moore |first=Frazier |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=October 26, 2013 |accessdate=June 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525075850/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/26/james-spader-megan-boone_n_4166497.html |archivedate=May 25, 2015 }}</ref> Producer Richard Heus said they chose to film specific Washington, D.C. locations for the series, including the [[Lincoln Memorial]], the [[Washington Monument]], and the [[National Mall]], because they were \"iconic American locations\".<ref name=\"Pilot Filming 2\">{{cite web|url=http://film.dc.gov/publication/interview-blacklist-producer-richard-heus|title=Interview with The Blacklist Producer Richard Heus|last=Gates|first=Angie|date=March 28, 2013|accessdate=June 16, 2015|publisher=Office of Motion Picture and Television Development}}</ref>\n\nThe series is filmed in [[4K resolution|4K]] using [[Sony]] PMW-F55 cameras that are adapted to use [[Panavision]] lenses.<ref name=\"Cameras Used\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtechnology.com/deployments/0108/k-in-the-tv-environment-where-it-is-now/269063|title=4K in the TV Environment: Where It Is Now|last=Soltz|first=Ned|date=March 4, 2014|accessdate=June 16, 2015|website=TV Technology|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208101040/http://www.tvtechnology.com/deployments/0108/k-in-the-tv-environment-where-it-is-now/269063|archivedate=December 8, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is edited using [[Media Composer|Avid Media Composer]], and editor Christopher Brookshire says the show has \"a very distinctive look and pace\".<ref name=\"Editing Software Used\">{{cite web|url=http://www.postmagazine.com/Publications/Post-Magazine/2015/January-1-2015/Primetime-NBCs-The-Blacklist.aspx|title=Primetime: NBC's 'The Blacklist'|last=Romanello|first=Linda|date=January 1, 2015|accessdate=June 16, 2015|work=Post Magazine}}</ref> An average of three cameras are used at one time, but as many as six cameras are sometimes recording.<ref name=\"Cameras Filming\">{{cite web|url=http://www.productionhub.com/blog/post/the-blacklist-short-lists-antonbauer-litepanels-and-oconnor|title='The Blacklist' Short Lists Anton/Bauer, Litepanels and OConnor|date=April 29, 2015|accessdate=June 16, 2015|website=ProductionHUB}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\nThe series is broadcast simultaneously on [[Global Television Network|Global]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|author=<!--Staff writer(s); No by-line-->|url=http://www.globaltv.com/theblacklist/|title=The Blacklist|website=[[Global Television Network]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Knox|first=David|title=The Blacklist Tops Monday But Homeland Sinks |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/10/the-blacklist-tops-monday-but-homeland-sinks.html|website=[[TV Tonight]]|date=October 1, 2013|access-date=May 22, 2015}}</ref> In New Zealand, the show premiered on [[TV3 (New Zealand)|TV3]] on February 2, 2014.<ref name=\"NZ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tv3.co.nz/Shows/TheBlacklist.aspx| title=The Blacklist|publisher=[[Mediaworks New Zealand]]|access-date=February 11, 2014}}</ref> The second season premiered on September 23.<ref>{{cite web|website=TV3|title=''The Blacklist''|url=http://www.tv3.co.nz/Shows/TheBlacklist.aspx}}</ref> In the United Kingdom and Ireland, the show premiered on [[Sky Witness]] (formally Sky Living) on October 4, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/09/sky-living-sets-uk-premiere-date-for-the-blacklist/|title=Sky Living Sets UK Premiere Date For 'The Blacklist'|last=Munn|first=Patrick|date=September 11, 2013|website=TV Wise|access-date=December 22, 2014}}</ref> The second season premiered on October 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2014/09/sky-living-sets-uk-premiere-date-blacklist-season-2/|title=Sky Living Sets UK Premiere Date For 'The Blacklist' Season 2|date=September 17, 2014|website=TV Wise|access-date=December 22, 2014}}</ref> But has since been moved to [[Sky One]]. [[Netflix]] has streaming rights to seasons 1\u20136 in the United States, Canada, Australia, Latin America, Finland, India, Switzerland, Germany, Sweden, The Netherlands, New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|title=When will Season 7 of The Blacklist be on Netflix?|url=https://www.whats-on-netflix.com/news/when-will-the-blacklist-season-7-be-on-netflix/|website=What's on Netflix|date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n\nThe first season of ''The Blacklist'' received strong reviews from television critics. On [[Metacritic]], the first season has a score of 74 out of 100, based on 31 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-blacklist/critic-reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|title=The Blacklist \u2013 Season 1 Reviews|accessdate = December 12, 2013}}</ref> The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports an 85% approval rating, based on 52 reviews, with an average score of 7.18/10. The consensus reads, \"James Spader is riveting as a criminal-turned-informant, and his presence goes a long way toward making this twisty but occasionally implausible crime procedural compelling\".<ref>{{cite web|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|title=The Blacklist: Season 1|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the-blacklist/s01/|accessdate=May 22, 2015}}</ref> The second season received a rating of 80%, based on 15 reviews, with an average score of 7.77/10. The consensus reads, \"Though ''The Blacklist'' flirts with narrative overload, it's held together by James Spader's scenery-eating performance and wildly entertaining action.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Blacklist: Season 2 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_blacklist/s02|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> The third season received a rating of 93%, based on 14 reviews, with an average score of 7.41/10. The consensus reads, \"''The Blacklist'' is back in top form with fresh dangers that put Red on the ropes while giving James Spader room to shine.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Blacklist: Season 3|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the-blacklist/s03/|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=June 23, 2016}}</ref> The fourth season received a rating of 88%, based on eight reviews, with an average score of 7/10.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Blacklist: Season 4 reviews|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_blacklist/s04|website=rottentomatoes.com|accessdate=Dec 7, 2017}}</ref> The fifth season received a rating of 100%, based on five reviews, with an average score of 8.5/10.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Blacklist: Season 5 reviews|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the_blacklist/s05|website=rottentomatoes.com|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' said about the pilot, \"You think you know this situation and how it will turn out, but there are surprising, yet entirely credible, twists throughout Monday's episode\".<ref name=\"Wiegand\" /> Robert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' said, \"''The Blacklist'' is a solid weekly crime show built around a genuine TV star. That's the kind of series the networks have to be able to pull off to survive. And with Spader in command, odds are NBC will\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Robert |last=Bianco |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/09/22/bianco-blacklist-hostages-combo-review-sept-23/2831619/ |title='Blacklist,' 'Hostages' each have suspenseful charms |newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=September 22, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2013}}</ref> Tim Goodman of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' praised both Spader's performance and the procedural elements of the show, writing \"there's an overarching element to the premise as well that makes it intriguing without making it overly complicated.\"<ref name=Goodman_blacklist>{{cite news|last1=Goodman|first1=Tim|title=The Blacklist: TV Review|date=September 19, 2013|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/blacklist-tv-review-632473|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{{Television season ratings\n| hide_18_49_rating=y\n| width                 = 90\n| link1            = The Blacklist (season 1)\n| timeslot1        = Monday 10:00&nbsp;p.m.\n| episodes1        = 22\n| start1           = {{Start date|2013|9|23}}\n| end1             = {{End date|2014|5|12}}\n| startrating1     = 12.58<ref name=S01E01>{{cite web |title=Monday Final TV Ratings: 'The Voice' & 'How I Met Your Mother' Adjusted Up; No Adjustment for 'Hostages' or 'The Blacklist' |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/09/24/monday-final-tv-ratings-the-voice-no-adjustment-for-hostages-or-the-blacklist/204423/ |last=Kondolojy |first=Amanda |website=TV by the Numbers |date=September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n| endrating1       = 10.44<ref name=S01E22>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/05/13/monday-final-tv-ratings-bones-castle-dancing-with-the-stars-star-crossed-adjusted-down/263656/|title=Monday Final TV Ratings: 'Bones', 'Castle', 'Dancing With The Stars' & 'Friends With Better Lives' Adjusted Up; 'Star-Crossed' Adjusted Down|last=Bibel|first=Sara|website=TV by the Numbers|date