{"title_page": "I Ain't No Miracle Worker", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Ain't No Miracle Worker\n| cover      = I Ain't No Miracle Worker.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Brogues]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Don't Shoot Me Down\n| released   = November 1965\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   = 1965, Sunset Recorders, [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist |\n* [[Garage rock]]\n* [[R&B]]\n* [[blues rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 2:51\n| label      = [[Challenge Records (1950s)|Challenge]]\n| writer     = [[Annette Tucker]], Nancie Mantz\n| producer   = Clara Thompson\n| prev_title = Somebody\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''I Ain't No Miracle Worker'''\" is a song by the American [[garage rock]] band, [[the Brogues]], written by [[Annette Tucker]] and Nancie Mantz, and released as the group's second and final [[single (music)|single]] on [[Challenge Records (1950s)|Challenge Records]], in November 1965 (''see'' [[1965 in music]]). The composition is now considered a classic of the musical genre of garage rock, and has reappeared on several [[compilation albums]] and has been [[cover versions|covered]] by other musical artists. The Brogues' original rendition was musically influenced by their contemporaries on the [[R&B]] circuit and the [[British Invasion]].\n\n==Background==\n\n===The Brogues version===\n[[The Brogues]] were hurried to record a follow-up [[single (music)|single]] after the regional success of their debut, \"Someday\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundazed.com/shop/product_info.php?products_id=2148|title=The Brogues|work=sundazed.com|accessdate=August 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905084516/http://www.sundazed.com/shop/product_info.php?products_id=2148|archive-date=September 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Over the span of a few months, the group's rebellious image and dynamic stage show launched them into prominence on the West Coast. In mid-1965, the band, bolstered by their addition of ex-Ratz [[lead vocalist]] Gary Cole, entered Sunset Recorders in Los Angeles to record \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\", which was penned by the songwriting duo of [[Annette Tucker]] and Nancie Mantz, coupled with \"Don't Shoot Me Down\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://60spunk.m78.com/brogues.htm|title=THE BROGUES MERCED MIRACLE WORKERS|work=60spunk.m78.com|author=Palao, Alex|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> The song's lyrics are about an individual who has no pretensions about himself and confesses in the subdued chorus \"I ain't no miracle worker\"/\"I do the best that I can\". The Brogues reworked Tucker's original instrumental arrangement with a jangling [[the Byrds|Byrds]]-inspired [[rhythm guitar|rhythm]] section and fuzz-toned guitar melody. The buzzing distorted sound was produced by [[lead guitarist]] Eddie Rodrigues's shredded [[Loudspeaker|speakers]] in his [[amplifier]]. In addition to the striking guitar [[motif (music)|motif]], the song is also marked by Cole's soulful vocal, Rick Campbell's [[electronic organ]] interjections, and Bill Whittington's heavy [[bass guitar|bass]] line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-aint-no-miracle-worker-mt0001708704|title=(I Ain't No) Miracle Worker - Review|work=allmusic.com|author=Planer, Lindsay|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=music>{{cite web|url=https://mercedmusic.wordpress.com/the-brogues/|title=Merced Music - The Brogues|work=mercedmusic.com|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" was released in November 1965 on the [[independent record label]], Challenge. Upon release however, the single failed to breakout nationally as a consequence of the record company's advertising focus being directed toward [[The Knickerbockers]]' hit, \"[[Lies (The Knickerbockers song)|Lies]]\". Additionally, the Brogues could not promote the single as they disbanded after two of their members were [[conscripted]] into the armed forces.<ref name=music/> Since its initial distribution, \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" is immortalized on the 1998 [[compact disc]] reissue of the [[compilation album]] ''[[Nuggets: Original Artyfacts from the First Psychedelic Era, 1965\u20131968]]'' and later ''[[Trash Box]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Nuggets: Original Artyfacts from the First Psychedelic Era, 1965\u20131968'' (CD booklet)|publisher=Sire Records|year=1998|author=Kaye, Lenny}}</ref> The [[B-side]], \"Don't Shoot Me Down\" is featured on ''[[Pebbles, Volume 10 (LP)|Pebbles, Volume 10]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-brogues-mn0000621990|title=The Brogues - Biography|work=allmusic.com|author=Montifchet, Stansted|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Other versions===\n[[The Chocolate Watchband]] recorded their own version of \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" in 1968 for their second [[album]] ''[[The Inner Mystique]]''. The group's rendition is swayed more toward [[psychedelia]] with its [[sitar]]-like guitar instrumentals played cohesively with its conventional [[rock music|rock]] arrangement. The song reaches a climax with lead vocalist David Aguilar's half-shouted chorus. In 2015, the Chocolate Watchband re-recorded the tune for the album ''I'm Not Like Everybody Else'', along with their other better-known tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-aint-no-miracle-worker-mt0014446680|title=I Ain't No Miracle Worker (The Chocolate Watchband) - Review|work=allmusic.com|author=Unterberger, Richie|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> Other versions of \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" were also released by the Italian [[beat music|beat group]] [[I Corvi]], which became their biggest hit, Jimmy and the Offbeats, [[Gene Pierson]], [[The Barracudas]], and [[Scott Miller (country musician)|Scott Miller]] & the Commonwealth (under the name \"Miracle Man\") on 2001's ''[[Thus Always to Tyrants (album)|Thus Always to Tyrants]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://secondhandsongs.com/performance/27132/versions|title=I Ain't No Miracle Worker by the Brogues|work=secondhandsongs.com|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1965 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Annette Tucker]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = I Ain't No Miracle Worker\n| cover      = I Ain't No Miracle Worker.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Brogues]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Don't Shoot Me Down\n| released   = November 1965\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   = 1965, Sunset Recorders, [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist |\n* [[Garage rock]]\n* [[R&B]]\n* [[blues rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 2:51\n| label      = [[Challenge Records (1950s)|Challenge]]\n| writer     = [[Annette Tucker]], Nancie Mantz\n| producer   = Clara Thompson\n| prev_title = Somebody\n| prev_year  = 1965\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''I Ain't No Miracle Worker'''\" is a song by the American [[garage rock]] band, [[the Brogues]], written by [[Annette Tucker]] and Nancie Mantz, and released as the group's second and final [[single (music)|single]] on [[Challenge Records (1950s)|Challenge Records]], in November 1965 (''see'' [[1965 in music]]). The composition is now considered a classic of the musical genre of garage rock, and has reappeared on several [[compilation albums]] and has been [[cover versions|covered]] by other musical artists. The Brogues' original rendition was musically influenced by their contemporaries on the [[R&B]] circuit and the [[British Invasion]].\n\n==Background==\n\n===The Brogues version===\n[[The Brogues]] were hurried to record a follow-up [[single (music)|single]] after the regional success of their debut, \"Someday\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundazed.com/shop/product_info.php?products_id=2148|title=The Brogues|work=sundazed.com|accessdate=August 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905084516/http://www.sundazed.com/shop/product_info.php?products_id=2148|archive-date=September 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Over the span of a few months, the group's rebellious image and dynamic stage show launched them into prominence on the West Coast. In mid-1965, the band, bolstered by their addition of ex-Ratz [[lead vocalist]] Gary Cole, entered Sunset Recorders in Los Angeles to record \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\", which was penned by the songwriting duo of [[Annette Tucker]] and Nancie Mantz, coupled with \"Don't Shoot Me Down\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://60spunk.m78.com/brogues.htm|title=THE BROGUES MERCED MIRACLE WORKERS|work=60spunk.m78.com|author=Palao, Alex|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> The song's lyrics are about an individual who has no pretensions about himself and confesses in the subdued chorus \"I ain't no miracle worker\"/\"I do the best that I can\". The Brogues reworked Tucker's original instrumental arrangement with a jangling [[the Byrds|Byrds]]-inspired [[rhythm guitar|rhythm]] section and fuzz-toned guitar melody. The buzzing distorted sound was produced by [[lead guitarist]] Eddie Rodrigues's shredded [[Loudspeaker|speakers]] in his [[amplifier]]. In addition to the striking guitar [[motif (music)|motif]], the song is also marked by Cole's soulful vocal, Rick Campbell's [[electronic organ]] interjections, and Bill Whittington's heavy [[bass guitar|bass]] line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-aint-no-miracle-worker-mt0001708704|title=(I Ain't No) Miracle Worker - Review|work=allmusic.com|author=Planer, Lindsay|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref><ref name=music>{{cite web|url=https://mercedmusic.wordpress.com/the-brogues/|title=Merced Music - The Brogues|work=mercedmusic.com|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n\"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" was released in November 1965 on the [[independent record label]], Challenge. Upon release however, the single failed to breakout nationally as a consequence of the record company's advertising focus being directed toward [[The Knickerbockers]]' hit, \"[[Lies (The Knickerbockers song)|Lies]]\". Additionally, the Brogues could not promote the single as they disbanded after two of their members were [[conscripted]] into the armed forces.<ref name=music/> Since its initial distribution, \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" is immortalized on the 1998 [[compact disc]] reissue of the [[compilation album]] ''[[Nuggets: Original Artyfacts from the First Psychedelic Era, 1965\u20131968]]'' and later ''[[Trash Box]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Nuggets: Original Artyfacts from the First Psychedelic Era, 1965\u20131968'' (CD booklet)|publisher=Sire Records|year=1998|author=Kaye, Lenny}}</ref> The [[B-side]], \"Don't Shoot Me Down\" is featured on ''[[Pebbles, Volume 10 (LP)|Pebbles, Volume 10]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-brogues-mn0000621990|title=The Brogues - Biography|work=allmusic.com|author=Montifchet, Stansted|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Other versions===\n[[The Chocolate Watchband]] recorded their own version of \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" in 1968 for their second [[album]] ''[[The Inner Mystique]]''. The group's rendition is swayed more toward [[psychedelia]] with its [[sitar]]-like guitar instrumentals played cohesively with its conventional [[rock music|rock]] arrangement. The song reaches a climax with lead vocalist David Aguillar's half-shouted chorus. In 2015, the Chocolate Watchband re-recorded the tune for the album ''I'm Not Like Everybody Else'', along with their other better-known tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/i-aint-no-miracle-worker-mt0014446680|title=I Ain't No Miracle Worker (The Chocolate Watchband) - Review|work=allmusic.com|author=Unterberger, Richie|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> Other versions of \"I Ain't No Miracle Worker\" were also released by the Italian [[beat music|beat group]] [[I Corvi]], which became their biggest hit, Jimmy and the Offbeats, [[Gene Pierson]], [[The Barracudas]], and [[Scott Miller (country musician)|Scott Miller]] & the Commonwealth (under the name \"Miracle Man\") on 2001's ''[[Thus Always to Tyrants (album)|Thus Always to Tyrants]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://secondhandsongs.com/performance/27132/versions|title=I Ain't No Miracle Worker by the Brogues|work=secondhandsongs.com|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1965 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Annette Tucker]]\n", "name_user": "Freewheeling frankie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther versions:Corrected spelling of Dave Aguilar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Ain%27t_No_Miracle_Worker"}
